            {
              "id": "022b63ea-ee16-3637-8691-8d5aae764e38",
              "name": "Cookie Lacks Secure, HttpOnly, And SameSite Flags",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an insecure session cookie configuration issue. In Python web applications, a cookie that carries authentication or session state should explicitly enable Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite protections so the browser applies the intended restrictions consistently.\n\nAt the shown sink, the application sets a session-style cookie containing encrypted user data but does not visibly set these flags. Without Secure, the cookie can be sent over non-HTTPS requests. Without HttpOnly, client-side scripts can read it if cross-site scripting is present. Without SameSite, the browser is more likely to attach the cookie to cross-site requests, increasing cross-site request forgery exposure.\n\nThe fix is to set all three attributes directly when calling set_cookie for this authentication cookie. Use Secure=True, HttpOnly=True, and an explicit SameSite value such as 'Lax' or 'Strict' based on the application flow. For login and session cookies, also limit scope with a narrow path and set a reasonable max_age or expires value if persistence is required.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nSet cookie security attributes explicitly on every authentication, session, and other sensitive cookie rather than relying on framework defaults. Use Secure so the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, HttpOnly to prevent JavaScript access, and SameSite='Lax' or 'Strict' to reduce cross-site request exposure. Prefer 'Strict' when the application does not require cross-site navigation to carry the session; otherwise use 'Lax' for typical login-backed browsing flows.\n\nApply these flags consistently wherever cookies are created, updated, or cleared. Ensure the application is served only over HTTPS, keep cookie scope as narrow as possible with path and domain settings, and avoid storing unnecessary sensitive data in the cookie even when encrypted.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nresponse.set_cookie(\n    key=\"vulpy_session\",\n    value=fernet.encrypt((username + \"|\" + country).encode()).decode(\"utf-8\"),\n    secure=True,\n    httponly=True,\n    samesite=\"Lax\",\n    path=\"/\"\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Response\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Secure Cookie Attribute](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/SecureCookieAttribute)\n- [OWASP HttpOnly](https://owasp.org/www-community/HttpOnly)\n- [OWASP SameSite](https://owasp.org/www-community/SameSite)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)\n- [Flask Response.set_cookie API](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/api/#flask.Response.set_cookie)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "04729de2-abc2-390f-b012-c5478da8adbb",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery in a state-changing Flask route. This POST endpoint enables MFA for the currently authenticated session and reads user-supplied form data, but there is no visible CSRF validation before the account state is changed.\n\nIn Flask applications that rely on session cookies, the browser will automatically attach those cookies to cross-site requests unless additional protections are enforced. That allows an attacker to cause a victim's browser to submit a forged POST to this route. Even though the route verifies an OTP, the request should still be bound to a trusted form submission from your application by validating a CSRF token and rejecting requests with an unexpected Origin or Referer.\n\nFor this handler, add route or application-level CSRF protection and include a CSRF token in the MFA enable form. As a defense in depth measure, verify that unsafe requests originate from your own site, and keep session cookies configured with Secure, HttpOnly, and an appropriate SameSite policy.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse framework-backed CSRF protection for every state-changing Flask route that accepts cookie-authenticated requests. In practice, enable CSRFProtect at the application layer or use FlaskForm with validate_on_submit() so the token is generated server-side, embedded in the form, and verified on POST before any account change occurs.\n\nFor sensitive actions such as enabling MFA, add a same-origin check on unsafe methods by validating the Origin header when present and falling back to Referer validation when needed. Also configure the session cookie with SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE = True, SESSION_COOKIE_HTTPONLY = True, and a restrictive SESSION_COOKIE_SAMESITE value so the browser is less likely to send authenticated cookies in cross-site contexts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Flask, abort, flash, g, redirect, render_template, request, url_for\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import StringField, SubmitField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired\nimport pyotp\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config['SECRET_KEY'] = 'change-this-secret-key'\napp.config['WTF_CSRF_TIME_LIMIT'] = 3600\ncsrf = CSRFProtect(app)\n\nclass MFAEnableForm(FlaskForm):\n    otp = StringField('OTP', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    submit = SubmitField('Enable MFA')\n\n\ndef _same_origin_required():\n    origin = request.headers.get('Origin')\n    host_url = request.host_url.rstrip('/')\n    if origin and origin.rstrip('/') != host_url:\n        abort(403)\n\n    referer = request.headers.get('Referer')\n    if not origin and referer and not referer.startswith(request.host_url):\n        abort(403)\n\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_mfa_enable():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    form = MFAEnableForm()\n\n    if form.validate_on_submit():\n        _same_origin_required()\n\n        secret = libmfa.mfa_get_secret(g.session['username'])\n        totp = pyotp.TOTP(secret)\n\n        if totp.verify(form.otp.data):\n            libmfa.mfa_enable(g.session['username'])\n            return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n        flash('The OTP was incorrect')\n        return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n    return render_template('mfa.enable.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\nFlask\npyotp\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Security Considerations](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/web-security/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "05a50fe8-ea34-3d2d-843f-c88f9dddaf30",
              "name": "Cookie Lacks Secure, HttpOnly, And SameSite Flags",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an insecure session cookie configuration issue. In Python web applications, setting an authentication or session cookie without explicitly enabling Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite weakens the browser-side protections around that cookie.\n\nWith a call like response.set_cookie('vulpy_session', session), the cookie may be sent over non-HTTPS connections if Secure is omitted, exposed to client-side script if HttpOnly is not set, and sent with cross-site requests if SameSite is left unset or too permissive. For a session identifier, these gaps increase the risk of session theft, cross-site request exploitation, and unauthorized account access.\n\nSet all three attributes explicitly when creating the session cookie. For this sink, mark the cookie as secure=True, httponly=True, and samesite='Lax' or 'Strict' unless a cross-site flow is required. If cross-site use is required, use samesite='None' only together with secure=True and only for cookies that truly need it.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nApply hardened defaults to every authentication and session cookie in the Python framework you use. Always set Secure so the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, HttpOnly to block access from JavaScript, and SameSite to reduce cross-site request exposure. Prefer SameSite='Lax' for normal session cookies and SameSite='Strict' for highly sensitive workflows that do not require cross-site navigation.\n\nUse SameSite='None' only when cross-site delivery is intentionally required, and only together with Secure. Review application-wide cookie helpers, middleware, and framework settings so these attributes are consistently enforced rather than relying on individual call sites. Also ensure the session cookie does not store sensitive data directly and rotate session identifiers after authentication events.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nresponse.set_cookie(\n    'vulpy_session',\n    session,\n    secure=True,\n    httponly=True,\n    samesite='Lax'\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom http import cookies\n\nNo additional dependencies required if the response object already supports set_cookie().\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Secure Cookie Attribute](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/SecureCookieAttribute)\n- [OWASP HttpOnly](https://owasp.org/www-community/HttpOnly)\n- [OWASP SameSite](https://owasp.org/www-community/SameSite)\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0c3e64a2-bf70-38b3-83ff-7367097fc8d1",
              "name": "Weak Or Broken Hash Function Used",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis code uses a weak cryptographic hash algorithm. In Python, calling hashlib.new(ALGORITHM, key).hexdigest() is unsafe when ALGORITHM can resolve to MD5 or SHA-1 for any security-sensitive purpose such as password handling, signatures, token derivation, or integrity checks.\n\nMD5 and SHA-1 are no longer considered secure against modern collision attacks, and plain fast hashes are also inappropriate for password storage. For the sink shown here, replace the dynamic weak algorithm selection with an explicit strong primitive. Use hashlib.sha256() or stronger for non-password hashing, use hmac.new(..., hashlib.sha256) when authenticity depends on a secret key, and use a password KDF such as hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac() when deriving or storing password-related values.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not allow security-sensitive hashing code to select algorithms dynamically from weak options. Replace MD5 and SHA-1 with SHA-256 or SHA-512 for general-purpose cryptographic hashing, and prefer direct constructors such as hashlib.sha256() over hashlib.new() when enforcing an approved algorithm.\n\nMatch the primitive to the use case. For password storage or password-derived values, use a password KDF with a unique salt and a high work factor, such as hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac(), scrypt, or Argon2. For integrity or authenticity tied to a secret, use HMAC with SHA-256 or better instead of hashing the secret and message directly. Store salts separately from passwords, keep secret keys out of source code, and compare security-sensitive digests with hmac.compare_digest().\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport hashlib\nimport hmac\nimport secrets\n\n# For non-password security-sensitive hashing, use an explicit strong algorithm.\nlastkey = hashlib.sha256(key).hexdigest()\n\n# If the value is keyed for integrity/authentication, use HMAC instead.\n# secret = b\"server-side-secret\"\n# lastkey = hmac.new(secret, key, hashlib.sha256).hexdigest()\n\n# If this is password-related, use a password KDF instead.\n# salt = secrets.token_bytes(16)\n# lastkey = hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac('sha256', key, salt, 600000).hex()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nhashlib\nhmac\nsecrets\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)\n- [Python hashlib documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html)\n- [Python hmac documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hmac.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "11fb13bd-f21c-3834-95e5-4098a20edc6a",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery in a state-changing Flask route. This handler accepts POST requests that change the authenticated user's password by reading request.form values, but there is no visible CSRF token validation before calling the password update logic.\n\nIn Flask, a browser will automatically send the user's session cookie with a cross-site form submission unless explicit protections are enforced. That means an attacker can trick a logged-in user into submitting a forged POST request to /chpasswd and cause an unintended password change. For this route, the correct fix is to require a CSRF token on the form and validate it on submission at the framework or route layer before processing request.form data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally for the Flask application and require a per-request token on every state-changing form. In templates, render the hidden CSRF field so POST requests to password change, profile update, logout, and similar endpoints are rejected if the token is missing or invalid.\n\nUse Flask-WTF's CSRFProtect with a strong SECRET_KEY, keep password changes on POST only, and prefer validate_on_submit() so token validation happens before business logic runs. For additional defense, set session cookies with Secure and SameSite=Lax or Strict as appropriate, and consider rejecting unsafe cross-site requests by validating Origin or Referer headers when a token cannot be used.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Flask, render_template, flash, session\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import PasswordField, SubmitField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired, EqualTo\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config['SECRET_KEY'] = 'replace-with-a-strong-random-secret'\napp.config['WTF_CSRF_TIME_LIMIT'] = 3600\ncsrf = CSRFProtect(app)\n\nclass ChangePasswordForm(FlaskForm):\n    password = PasswordField('New password', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    password_again = PasswordField(\n        'Repeat password',\n        validators=[DataRequired(), EqualTo('password', message=\"The passwords don't match\")]\n    )\n    submit = SubmitField('Change password')\n\n@mod_user.route('/chpasswd', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_chpasswd():\n    form = ChangePasswordForm()\n\n    if form.validate_on_submit():\n        password = form.password.data\n\n        if not libuser.password_complexity(password):\n            flash(\"The password doesn't comply with complexity requirements\")\n            return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form)\n\n        libuser.password_change(session['username'], password)\n        flash('Password changed')\n        return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form)\n\n    return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Security Considerations](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/web-security/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "14bbcf82-8d6c-3281-8852-b4c567abfced",
              "name": "Weak Or Broken Hash Function Used",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure hash algorithm usage. In Python, calling hashlib.new(ALGORITHM, response.encode()).hexdigest() with MD5 or SHA-1 creates a digest using algorithms that are no longer appropriate for security-sensitive purposes such as password hashing, signatures, or integrity checks against active attackers.\n\nThis sink is especially risky because the algorithm is selected dynamically. If ALGORITHM can resolve to md5 or sha1, the code may produce collision-prone or brute-force-friendly hashes. For general integrity or security tokens, use SHA-256 or stronger. If the value being hashed is a password or other user secret, replace the direct hash with a password KDF such as PBKDF2-HMAC using a unique random salt and a high iteration count.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not allow weak hash names such as md5 or sha1 to flow into hashlib.new for security decisions. Prefer a fixed allowlist of strong algorithms, with hashlib.sha256 or hashlib.sha512 for general-purpose hashing. Avoid algorithm agility unless there is a clear compatibility requirement and strict validation.\n\nIf the hashed value is a password, API key, or similar secret, do not use a plain fast hash at all. Use a password hashing function or KDF with a per-value random salt and a work factor high enough for current hardware. In Python, hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac is available in the standard library; store the salt and iteration count alongside the derived value.\n\nIf this hash is used only for non-security tasks such as partitioning or deduplication, document that purpose clearly and keep the code path separate from any security-sensitive use so weak algorithms are not reused accidentally.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport hashlib\nimport hmac\nimport os\n\n# For non-password security hashing, use a strong fixed algorithm.\nresult = hashlib.sha256(response.encode(\"utf-8\")).hexdigest()\n\n# If this value is a password or secret, use a password KDF instead.\nsalt = os.urandom(16)\nderived_key = hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac(\n    \"sha256\",\n    response.encode(\"utf-8\"),\n    salt,\n    600000\n)\npassword_hash = derived_key.hex()\n\n# When comparing stored digests, use constant-time comparison.\nis_match = hmac.compare_digest(result, hashlib.sha256(response.encode(\"utf-8\")).hexdigest())\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nhashlib\nhmac\nos\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)\n- [Python hashlib documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html)\n- [Python pbkdf2_hmac documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html#hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "152024d8-de8a-3c1a-a12f-6f3885fe83da",
              "name": "Hardcoded Configuration Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded secret in application configuration. In Python web applications, embedding a Flask SECRET_KEY directly in source code exposes a sensitive value to anyone who can read the repository, logs, backups, or deployed artifacts. If that key is reused across environments or leaked, attackers can tamper with signed session data and other security-sensitive application features that depend on the secret.\n\nFor the shown sink, assigning app.config['SECRET_KEY'] to a literal string should be replaced with loading the secret from the environment or a protected configuration source at runtime. This keeps the key out of version control and allows separate secrets per environment. The application should also fail fast if the variable is missing, rather than silently using an insecure default.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nStore secrets outside the codebase and inject them at deployment time using environment variables, a secrets manager, or protected instance configuration. Use a strong randomly generated value for each environment, rotate it if exposure is suspected, and never commit sample production secrets to source control. In Flask, load the secret during startup and raise an error when it is absent so the application cannot run with an unsafe fallback.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\nsecret_key = os.environ[\"SECRET_KEY\"]\napp.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"] = secret_key\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Use of Hard-coded Password](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)\n- [Flask Documentation: Configuration Handling](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#configuration-basics)\n- [Python Documentation: os.environ](https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1b24daf2-bb73-3e6f-b304-834a1ac59af6",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Writing directly to a predictable path such as /tmp/ca.pub in Python can let another local user pre-create the file, replace it with a symlink, or read or overwrite its contents depending on filesystem permissions.\n\nThe sink shown uses open() on a shared temporary directory with a fixed filename. In a multi-user environment this creates a race condition and can cause unauthorized disclosure or modification of the public key file, or unintended writes to another file if the path is redirected through a link. The fix is to create the file securely with Python's tempfile APIs or to write into an application-controlled directory with restrictive permissions.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hard-coded filenames under shared temporary directories such as /tmp. Use tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile, tempfile.mkstemp, or tempfile.TemporaryDirectory so the filename is generated unpredictably and opened atomically. When the file must persist after closing, mkstemp is a good fit because it returns an already-open file descriptor.\n\nApply restrictive permissions when creating the file, and prefer an application-owned directory over a world-writable location when possible. If the data is only needed briefly, delete the file as soon as processing completes. Also avoid following user-controlled paths or symlinks for temporary storage.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, temp_path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"ca_\", suffix=\".pub\")\ntry:\n    os.fchmod(fd, 0o600)\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as out:\n        out.write(ca_public_key_bytes)\nfinally:\n    pass\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\nreferences\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1b5f7e3d-e6d9-3352-8bec-5afff4e82c69",
              "name": "Insecure HTTP Transport Used",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an insecure transport issue: the code sends an HTTP request over an unencrypted connection. In Python, using requests.post() with an http:// URL allows anyone on the network path to read or tamper with the transmitted data.\n\nIn the shown sink, the request body includes a username and password. Sending credentials over cleartext HTTP exposes them to interception and session compromise. The fix is to use an https:// endpoint and keep TLS certificate verification enabled so the client both encrypts the traffic and verifies the server identity.\n\nIf the URL is built from configuration, enforce HTTPS before making the request and fail closed when a non-TLS scheme is supplied. This is especially important for authentication and other sensitive POST requests.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse HTTPS for all outbound requests that carry credentials, tokens, session identifiers, or other sensitive data. Do not allow fallback to http://, and do not disable TLS certificate verification with verify=False. Validate configured endpoints at startup or immediately before use so insecure schemes are rejected consistently.\n\nPrefer storing service endpoints as HTTPS URLs in configuration, and use reasonable request timeouts and error handling. If internal services currently expose only HTTP, place them behind TLS rather than sending secrets across the network in cleartext.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom urllib.parse import urlparse\nimport requests\n\nparsed = urlparse(URL)\nif parsed.scheme.lower() != \"https\":\n    raise ValueError(\"Refusing to send credentials over a non-HTTPS connection\")\n\nresponse = requests.post(\n    URL,\n    data={\"username\": username, \"password\": password},\n    timeout=10,\n)\nresponse.raise_for_status()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nrequests\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insecure Transport](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Transport)\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Security Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)\n- [Requests: SSL Cert Verification](https://requests.readthedocs.io/en/latest/user/advanced/#ssl-cert-verification)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "3.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1c747a52-dc56-3fd6-b7a4-396cd7c05fe9",
              "name": "Insecure Password Storage in SQL Authentication",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is insecure password verification and unsafe SQL query construction. In Python, comparing a supplied password directly to a database password column implies the application is storing passwords in a recoverable or plaintext form, and building the query with string formatting also exposes the login path to SQL injection.\n\nFor the sink shown, the fix is to query by username only with a parameterized statement, retrieve the stored password hash, and verify the supplied password in application code using a modern password hashing algorithm such as Argon2. This separates authentication logic from SQL text, prevents direct password comparisons in the database, and avoids embedding untrusted input into the query string.\n\nWhen updating existing records, store only salted password hashes generated by the password hashing library. Never store raw passwords, reversible encryption of passwords, or hashes produced by fast general-purpose algorithms such as MD5 or SHA-1 for authentication purposes.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized SQL for all database access, including authentication queries. Do not interpolate username or password values into SQL strings with format, f-strings, or concatenation.\n\nStore passwords only as salted password hashes produced by a dedicated password hashing algorithm such as Argon2, bcrypt, or PBKDF2. Fetch the account record by a unique identifier such as username, then verify the supplied password with the hashing library in Python code. If the application currently stores plaintext passwords, force a credential reset or migrate users carefully at next login by replacing the stored value with a fresh password hash.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom argon2 import PasswordHasher\nfrom argon2.exceptions import VerifyMismatchError\nimport sqlite3\n\nph = PasswordHasher()\nconn = sqlite3.connect(\"app.db\")\nc = conn.cursor()\n\ndef authenticate(username: str, password: str):\n    row = c.execute(\n        \"SELECT id, username, password_hash FROM users WHERE username = ?\",\n        (username,)\n    ).fetchone()\n\n    if row is None:\n        return None\n\n    user_id, db_username, password_hash = row\n\n    try:\n        ph.verify(password_hash, password)\n        if ph.check_needs_rehash(password_hash):\n            new_hash = ph.hash(password)\n            c.execute(\n                \"UPDATE users SET password_hash = ? WHERE id = ?\",\n                (new_hash, user_id)\n            )\n            conn.commit()\n        return row\n    except VerifyMismatchError:\n        return None\n\ndef create_user(username: str, password: str):\n    password_hash = ph.hash(password)\n    c.execute(\n        \"INSERT INTO users (username, password_hash) VALUES (?, ?)\",\n        (username, password_hash)\n    )\n    conn.commit()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nargon2-cffi\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-256: Plaintext Storage of a Password](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [argon2-cffi documentation](https://argon2-cffi.readthedocs.io/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-256",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-256",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "28df7bb0-3233-331b-b390-448242299ead",
              "name": "Insecure Client Cookie Handling Without Signing",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an unsigned client-side session cookie issue. In this Python code, application state is converted to JSON, base64-encoded, and written directly into a cookie. Base64 is only an encoding step, so a client can read and modify the cookie contents before sending it back.\n\nWhen session state such as a username is stored this way, the server has no integrity protection to detect tampering. An attacker can change the serialized value and impersonate another user or alter application behavior. If confidentiality is also required, the value must be protected with authenticated encryption rather than plain serialization.\n\nFor the sink shown here, the safest fix is to stop storing authoritative session state in the cookie value and instead store only a random session identifier, with the real session data kept on the server. If client-side state must be used, sign it or encrypt it with authentication using a managed secret key stored outside source code, and set secure cookie attributes.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not place trusted session state directly into client cookies as raw JSON or base64 text. Use a server-side session store keyed by a cryptographically random session identifier, and rotate or expire sessions according to application policy. Mark session cookies HttpOnly, Secure, and with an appropriate SameSite value.\n\nIf the design requires client-stored state, protect it with authenticated encryption or at minimum a strong server-side signature using a well-maintained Python library. Keep encryption or signing keys in environment-backed secret management, not in source code or static configuration checked into the repository. Reject malformed, expired, or unverifiable tokens and avoid storing sensitive data in cookies unless there is a clear need.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport secrets\n\nsession_id = secrets.token_urlsafe(32)\nserver_session_store[session_id] = {\"username\": username}\nresponse.set_cookie(\n    \"vulpy_session\",\n    session_id,\n    httponly=True,\n    secure=True,\n    samesite=\"Lax\"\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ncryptography\nFlask-Session\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Secure Cookie Attribute](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/SecureCookieAttribute)\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-565: Reliance on Cookies without Validation and Integrity Checking](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/565.html)\n- [cryptography.io Fernet documentation](https://cryptography.io/en/latest/fernet/)\n- [Flask session documentation](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/quickstart/#sessions)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-565",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/565.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-565"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "37edff6f-5d83-3078-80c5-aa0f2ffb8867",
              "name": "Insecure Authentication Using Header-Derived Tokens",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an improper authentication issue. The code treats an untrusted request header as proof of identity, searches the filesystem using that header value, and derives the authenticated principal from a matching filename.\n\nIn Python, this pattern is unsafe because any client that can guess, reuse, or manipulate the X-APIKEY value can influence authentication. Using the header directly in a glob pattern also mixes identity lookup with filesystem naming, which is brittle and can expose accounts through predictable files or accidental matches. Authentication decisions should not depend on filenames in /tmp or other writable paths.\n\nReplace this logic with explicit token validation. For API keys, store a server-generated key identifier and a salted hash in a database, then compare the presented key against stored records using constant-time comparison. If you use bearer tokens, verify a signed token with a trusted secret or public key and read identity from validated claims rather than from filesystem artifacts.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not authenticate users by matching untrusted header values against filenames or by deriving identity from path names. Keep authentication state in a dedicated trust boundary such as a database or a signed token verifier. Generate high-entropy API keys with the secrets module, store only a salted hash of the key, associate it with an explicit account record, and reject revoked or expired credentials.\n\nIf bearer tokens are used, require an Authorization header, verify the signature, issuer, audience, expiration, and algorithm with a well-maintained JWT library, and then map validated claims to an application user. Avoid using /tmp for identity data, avoid wildcard filesystem lookups during authentication, and use constant-time comparison for credential checks. Log failed authentication attempts without recording full secrets.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport hashlib\nimport hmac\nimport os\nimport sqlite3\nfrom secrets import compare_digest\nfrom flask import abort, request\n\nDB_PATH = os.environ.get(\"AUTH_DB_PATH\", \"auth.db\")\n\n\ndef _hash_api_key(api_key: str, salt: bytes) -> bytes:\n    return hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac(\"sha256\", api_key.encode(\"utf-8\"), salt, 200_000)\n\n\ndef authenticate_request() -> str:\n    api_key = request.headers.get(\"X-APIKEY\")\n    if not api_key:\n        abort(401)\n\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(DB_PATH)\n    try:\n        row = conn.execute(\n            \"SELECT username, key_salt, key_hash, revoked FROM api_keys WHERE key_id = ?\",\n            (\"primary\",)\n        ).fetchone()\n    finally:\n        conn.close()\n\n    if row is None:\n        abort(401)\n\n    username, key_salt, key_hash, revoked = row\n    if revoked:\n        abort(401)\n\n    expected_hash = _hash_api_key(api_key, key_salt)\n    if not compare_digest(expected_hash, key_hash):\n        abort(401)\n\n    return username\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nPyJWT\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP API Security Top 10 2023 - Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/API-Security/editions/2023/en/0xa2-broken-authentication/)\n- [OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authentication_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-287: Improper Authentication](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/287.html)\n- [Python secrets module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/secrets.html)\n- [PyJWT Usage Examples](https://pyjwt.readthedocs.io/en/stable/usage.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-287",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/287.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-287"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "38cd48cb-eb70-31c6-bbdf-90e8253d959b",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery protection is missing on a state-changing Flask route. This endpoint accepts POST form data and performs an account-creation action, but there is no visible verification of a CSRF token and no request-origin validation before processing the submitted form.\n\nIn Flask applications, a browser will automatically include cookies and other ambient credentials when submitting a cross-site request. If a victim is authenticated or otherwise has an active session, an attacker can cause the browser to submit a forged POST request to this route and create accounts or trigger other unwanted state changes. The route should require a server-generated CSRF token for POST requests and reject requests that fail validation.\n\nFor this handler, the most reliable fix is to enable CSRF protection at the framework layer and render a hidden CSRF token in the HTML form used by user.create.html. If you need an additional defense, validate the Origin or Referer header for unsafe methods and keep the route limited to POST for submission handling.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse framework-enforced CSRF protection for every route that changes server state, including account creation, password changes, and delete actions. In Flask, the standard approach is to enable Flask-WTF CSRFProtect, use a form class for POST handling, and include the hidden CSRF field in the rendered template. This gives consistent token generation and validation without hand-written checks.\n\nDo not rely on GET for state changes, and keep unsafe actions behind POST, PUT, PATCH, or DELETE with CSRF validation. As a second layer of defense, verify Origin or Referer headers for unsafe methods, set session cookies with Secure and SameSite protections where compatible, and ensure SECRET_KEY is strong and kept out of source control.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, flash, redirect, render_template, request, session, url_for\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import PasswordField, StringField, SubmitField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\nmod_user = Blueprint('mod_user', __name__)\n\n\nclass CreateUserForm(FlaskForm):\n    username = StringField('Username', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    password = PasswordField('Password', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    submit = SubmitField('Create user')\n\n\n@mod_user.route('/create', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_create():\n    session.pop('username', None)\n    form = CreateUserForm()\n\n    if form.validate_on_submit():\n        username = form.username.data\n        password = form.password.data\n\n        libuser.create(username, password)\n        flash('User created. Please login.')\n        return redirect(url_for('mod_user.do_login'))\n\n    if request.method == 'POST' and not form.validate():\n        flash('Please, complete username and password')\n\n    return render_template('user.create.html', form=form)\n\n\n# application setup\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config['SECRET_KEY'] = 'replace-with-a-long-random-secret'\ncsrf.init_app(app)\napp.register_blueprint(mod_user)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Security Considerations](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/web-security/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3abff929-ab68-3bb1-a6a0-29b606b74141",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an insecure temporary file handling issue. In Python, writing directly to a predictable path such as /tmp/acme.pub allows other local users or processes to interfere with the file through pre-creation, symlink attacks, overwrites, or unintended reads.\n\nThe sink shown uses open() on a hard-coded name in a shared temporary directory. On multi-user systems, /tmp is typically world-writable, so an attacker can race the application, replace the path with a symbolic link, or read the file if permissions are too broad. The safer approach is to let Python create the file atomically with a unique name and restrictive permissions.\n\nUse the tempfile module to create the file securely, write the contents through the returned file descriptor, and, if a stable final path is required, move the file into place with an atomic rename after validating the destination. This avoids predictable names in shared directories and reduces exposure to local file-system attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not create temporary files by concatenating fixed names under /tmp or other shared writable directories. Use tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile, tempfile.mkstemp, or TemporaryDirectory so the operating system creates a unique file atomically with safe permissions. Keep temporary files in a directory not writable by untrusted users whenever possible.\n\nIf the file must end up at a known path, write it first to a securely created temporary file and then move it into place with os.replace. Ensure the target directory has appropriate ownership and permissions, avoid following symlinks when handling sensitive files, and delete temporary artifacts promptly after use.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, temp_path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"acme_\", suffix=\".pub\")\ntry:\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as out:\n        out.write(public_key_bytes)\n\n    final_path = \"/var/lib/acme/acme.pub\"\n    os.replace(temp_path, final_path)\nfinally:\n    if os.path.exists(temp_path):\n        os.unlink(temp_path)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3ac8edf6-5510-3295-b417-abbf726cd12c",
              "name": "Debug Mode Enabled In Production Environment",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an active debug mode in production vulnerability. In Python Flask applications, starting the development server with debug enabled can expose stack traces, configuration details, environment data, and other sensitive internals to users when errors occur.\n\nIn the shown sink, the application is launched with app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', ssl_context=(...)). Even when TLS is configured, debug mode still enables development-only behavior that is unsafe outside local development. The fix is to disable debug explicitly in code and drive environment-specific behavior through Flask configuration or environment variables, while using a production WSGI server for deployment.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not hardcode debug=True in Flask startup code. Default DEBUG to false and only enable it in a controlled local development environment through configuration or environment variables. For deployed environments, serve the application with a production-grade WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI instead of relying on Flask's built-in development server. Keep detailed error information in server-side logs and return generic error responses to clients.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config.from_mapping(\n    DEBUG=os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\"\n)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    app.run(\n        debug=app.config[\"DEBUG\"],\n        host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n        ssl_context=(\"/tmp/acme.cert\", \"/tmp/acme.key\")\n    )\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask\ngunicorn\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Flask Documentation: Debug Mode](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#debug-mode)\n- [OWASP: Information Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Information_exposure_through_query_strings_in_url)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3c9566d8-c680-3db8-b643-79579cc1051c",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery in a state-changing Flask POST route. This handler creates a post using the authenticated session and trusts form data from any POST request, but it does not show a CSRF token check or a same-origin validation step before calling the write operation.\n\nIn Flask applications, session cookies are sent automatically by the browser. Without CSRF protection, an attacker can cause a logged-in user to submit a forged POST request from another site, resulting in unintended content creation under that user's account. For this route, the fix is to enforce CSRF validation at the framework level and require a token on the form that submits text.\n\nA robust remediation is to enable Flask-WTF CSRFProtect for the application and validate a hidden csrf_token field on the form rendered to the user. As defense in depth, keep the route restricted to POST for state changes and consider rejecting cross-origin requests by checking Origin or Referer when appropriate.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally for the Flask application rather than trying to protect individual handlers manually. For HTML form workflows, use Flask-WTF CSRFProtect and FlaskForm so POST requests are rejected unless they include a valid per-session token. Ensure the form template renders the hidden token field with form.hidden_tag() or the csrf_token field explicitly.\n\nKeep state-changing actions limited to POST, PUT, PATCH, or DELETE, and do not rely on checking request.method alone as a CSRF defense. If some endpoints are not form-based, add a same-origin check using the Origin header, or Referer as a fallback, and set session cookies with Secure and SameSite=Lax or Strict where compatible. Avoid disabling CSRF on authenticated routes that modify server state.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Flask, Blueprint, g, redirect, render_template, request\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import TextAreaField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired, Length\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config['SECRET_KEY'] = 'replace-with-a-strong-random-secret'\ncsrf = CSRFProtect(app)\n\nmod_posts = Blueprint('posts', __name__)\n\n\nclass PostForm(FlaskForm):\n    text = TextAreaField(validators=[DataRequired(), Length(max=5000)])\n\n\n@mod_posts.route('/', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_create():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    form = PostForm()\n    if form.validate_on_submit():\n        username = g.session['username']\n        libposts.post(username, form.text.data)\n        return redirect('/')\n\n    return render_template('create_post.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://owasp.org/www-project-cheat-sheets/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Security Considerations](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/web-security/)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "42df2164-279b-3d58-9e07-0fd2b1f9117a",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery protection is missing on a state-changing Flask route. This login endpoint accepts POSTed form data and creates an authenticated session, but there is no visible CSRF validation before processing username, password, and OTP input.\n\nIn Flask applications, a form POST that changes authentication state should require a per-request or per-session CSRF token and reject requests that do not present a valid token. Without that check, a browser can be induced to submit a forged request with the victim's cookies attached, which can lead to unwanted login flows or session state manipulation.\n\nFor this route, enable framework-level CSRF protection and render the token in the login form. If the application has routes that cannot use form tokens, add a strict Origin or Referer validation fallback for HTTPS requests, but prefer token-based protection for browser form submissions.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse CSRF protection for every browser-accessible POST, PUT, PATCH, and DELETE route that changes authentication or server state. In Flask, the standard fix is to enable CSRFProtect for the application and use FlaskForm so token generation and validation happen automatically. Ensure the template includes the hidden CSRF field and that the application has a strong SECRET_KEY.\n\nDo not rely on cookies alone to protect login or session-establishing endpoints. Keep session cookies configured with Secure, HttpOnly, and an appropriate SameSite value, but treat those settings as defense in depth rather than a replacement for CSRF tokens. Where a token cannot be used, validate Origin and, if necessary, Referer against the expected scheme and host for HTTPS requests and reject mismatches.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, flash, make_response, redirect, render_template, request, session\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import PasswordField, StringField, SubmitField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\nmod_user = Blueprint('mod_user', __name__)\n\n\nclass LoginForm(FlaskForm):\n    username = StringField('Username', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    password = PasswordField('Password', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    otp = StringField('OTP')\n    submit = SubmitField('Sign in')\n\n\n@mod_user.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_login():\n    form = LoginForm()\n\n    if form.validate_on_submit():\n        session.pop('username', None)\n\n        username = libuser.login(form.username.data, form.password.data)\n\n        if not username:\n            flash('Invalid user or password')\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html', form=form), 400\n\n        if libmfa.mfa_is_enabled(username):\n            if not libmfa.mfa_validate(username, form.otp.data):\n                flash('Invalid OTP')\n                return render_template('user.login.mfa.html', form=form), 400\n\n        response = make_response(redirect('/'))\n        response = libsession.create(request=request, response=response, username=username)\n        return response\n\n    return render_template('user.login.mfa.html', form=form)\n\n# application setup\n# app = Flask(__name__)\n# app.config['SECRET_KEY'] = 'set-a-strong-secret-key'\n# csrf.init_app(app)\n\n# template excerpt: user.login.mfa.html\n# <form method=\"post\">\n#   {{ form.csrf_token }}\n#   {{ form.username() }}\n#   {{ form.password() }}\n#   {{ form.otp() }}\n#   {{ form.submit() }}\n# </form>\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "43b0aaf2-a164-3bd6-92ad-143ecf2443d8",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery in a state-changing Flask POST route. This handler accepts form data and performs a write operation with the current session user, but there is no visible CSRF validation before calling the state-changing function.\n\nIn Flask, a browser will automatically include the victim's session cookie when a malicious site submits a forged POST request to this endpoint. Because the route trusts the authenticated session and reads request.form directly, an attacker can cause an unwanted post to be created on behalf of the logged-in user.\n\nProtect this route by enabling CSRF validation at the framework layer and requiring a per-request token on HTML forms. For additional defense in depth, reject unsafe cross-origin requests by checking the Origin header and only allowing your own host. This is well suited to the shown sink because the route is a form-backed POST endpoint that mutates server-side state.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally for the Flask application rather than handling individual routes manually. For server-rendered forms, include a CSRF token in every state-changing form and let the framework validate it automatically on POST, PUT, PATCH, and DELETE requests. Avoid relying on request.method checks alone, because they do not verify request origin or user intent.\n\nUse defense in depth by validating the Origin header for unsafe methods and by setting session cookies with Secure, HttpOnly, and an appropriate SameSite policy. Keep state-changing actions off GET routes, ensure login state is checked with session.get to avoid exceptions, and prefer Flask-WTF or equivalent middleware over custom token logic unless there is a strong reason to build your own.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom urllib.parse import urlparse\n\nfrom flask import Flask, abort, redirect, request, session\nfrom flask_wtf.csrf import CSRFProtect\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"] = \"change-me-to-a-strong-random-secret\"\napp.config[\"WTF_CSRF_TIME_LIMIT\"] = 3600\ncsrf = CSRFProtect(app)\n\n\ndef _same_origin(req):\n    origin = req.headers.get(\"Origin\")\n    if not origin:\n        return False\n    origin_host = urlparse(origin).netloc\n    return origin_host == req.host\n\n\n@app.route(\"/post\", methods=[\"POST\"])\ndef do_post():\n    if not session.get(\"username\"):\n        return redirect(\"/user/login\")\n\n    if not _same_origin(request):\n        abort(403)\n\n    username = session[\"username\"]\n    text = request.form.get(\"text\", \"\")\n    post(username, text)\n    return redirect(\"/\")\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nFlask\nitsdangerous\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Security Considerations](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/web-security/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "455b8595-f03d-32c2-92fa-f948c17d8314",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Reading sensitive material from a fixed path under /tmp is unsafe in Python because that directory is typically shared by multiple users and processes, and predictable names such as /tmp/acme.key are vulnerable to symlink attacks, file replacement, race conditions, and unintended disclosure.\n\nIn this sink, the code opens a key file from a world-writable temporary location using a hard-coded filename. An attacker who can write to /tmp may create or replace that path before it is opened, causing the application to read attacker-controlled content or expose secret key material. Mitigate this by storing key files outside shared temporary directories, creating them with restrictive permissions, and validating that the path refers to the expected regular file before use.\n\nIf temporary storage is required, use Python's tempfile APIs to create a unique file or directory securely, restrict permissions to the current user, and avoid predictable names. For long-lived keys, prefer an application-controlled directory such as one under the user's home directory or a protected service-specific data directory instead of /tmp.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not place secrets or trust-sensitive files at predictable names in shared temporary directories such as /tmp. Use a protected application directory with owner-only permissions for persistent keys. When temporary files are necessary, create them with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile, tempfile.mkstemp, or tempfile.TemporaryDirectory so the name is unique and creation is atomic.\n\nBefore opening an existing key file, verify that it is a regular file, not a symlink, and that its permissions do not allow group or world access. Keep the file outside publicly writable locations, ensure the parent directory is also restricted, and avoid following user-controlled paths for security-sensitive reads.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nimport stat\n\nkey_path = Path.home() / \".acme\" / \"acme.key\"\nkey_path.parent.mkdir(mode=0o700, parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n\nfile_stat = key_path.stat()\nif not stat.S_ISREG(file_stat.st_mode):\n    raise ValueError(\"Key path must be a regular file\")\nif file_stat.st_mode & 0o077:\n    raise PermissionError(\"Key file permissions must be restricted to the owner\")\n\nwith key_path.open(\"rb\") as key_file:\n    key_data = key_file.read()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nimport stat\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [Python pathlib — Object-oriented filesystem paths](https://docs.python.org/3/library/pathlib.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4bc5d952-6423-3b33-b913-4b1c5d4ef11b",
              "name": "Flask App Running In Debug Mode",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure debug mode in a production web server. In Flask, calling app.run(debug=True) enables the interactive Werkzeug debugger, which can expose detailed stack traces, environment data, and in some configurations permit arbitrary code execution from the debug console.\n\nFor the shown sink, the application is explicitly started with debug mode enabled while also binding to a network interface and serving TLS material from local certificate files. Even if the host is intended to be limited, debug mode must not be enabled outside local development. Run the application with debug disabled, load the setting from a trusted configuration source, and use a production WSGI server for deployed environments instead of the built-in development server.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not hardcode debug=True in Flask startup code. Keep the debugger disabled by default and only enable it for local development through trusted environment-specific configuration. For deployed systems, run Flask behind a production-grade WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI, restrict network exposure, and ensure stack traces and interactive consoles are never accessible to end users. Also store TLS private keys outside temporary locations and apply file permissions that limit access to the service account.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    debug = os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\" and os.getenv(\"FLASK_ENV\") == \"development\"\n\n    app.run(\n        debug=debug,\n        host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n        ssl_context=(\"/tmp/acme.cert\", \"/tmp/acme.key\")\n    )\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation - Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Werkzeug Documentation - Debugger](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debug/)\n- [OWASP REST Security Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/REST_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4dd49418-d538-387d-9f7b-7a5ac9b7ff8b",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. In Python, storing sensitive material such as an API key in a predictable path under /tmp exposes it to disclosure, overwrite, race-condition, and symlink attacks because that directory is shared and the filename is easy to guess.\n\nThe sink shown uses Path('/tmp/supersecret.txt'), which creates a fixed location for secret data instead of a securely created temporary file. Use the tempfile module to create a file with restrictive permissions and an unpredictable name, or store the secret in memory or a protected application-specific directory when persistence is required.\n\nIf the file must exist on disk, ensure it is created atomically, limit permissions to the current user, and delete it as soon as it is no longer needed. Avoid hard-coded temporary paths for credentials and other secrets.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not place secrets in predictable filenames under shared temporary directories such as /tmp. In Python, prefer tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile, tempfile.mkstemp, or tempfile.TemporaryDirectory to obtain a unique path created securely by the operating system. Keep secrets in memory when possible, and if disk storage is unavoidable, create the file atomically, set permissions to owner-only, avoid following symlinks, and remove the file promptly after use. For longer-lived secret storage, use a protected application directory outside world-writable locations.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom tempfile import NamedTemporaryFile\n\nwith NamedTemporaryFile(mode=\"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\", delete=False) as tmp:\n    api_key_file = Path(tmp.name)\n    tmp.write(api_key)\n\napi_key_file.chmod(0o600)\n\n# Remove the file when it is no longer needed.\n# api_key_file.unlink()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom tempfile import NamedTemporaryFile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [Python pathlib documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/pathlib.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "503f541e-1c03-3b09-a96c-20998c31a0ef",
              "name": "Missing Function Level Access Control",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nMissing function-level access control. This view processes a session cookie and returns user identity data, but it does not enforce authentication or authorization at the entry point. Relying on inline cookie parsing alone is not a substitute for framework-level access control, because the function can be invoked without an authenticated session context and there is no explicit policy deciding who is allowed to call it.\n\nIn Python web applications, access checks should be applied consistently at the route or view boundary with the framework's authentication and authorization mechanisms. For this function, require a logged-in user before executing the handler, validate the user through the server-side session or established authentication backend, and return an HTTP authorization error instead of an empty object when access is denied. If the endpoint is intended only for the current user, derive identity from the authenticated request context rather than trusting a manually decrypted cookie payload.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nProtect the handler with the web framework's authentication decorator or middleware so unauthenticated requests are rejected before the function body runs. Perform authorization checks server-side for the specific action or resource, and base those checks on trusted request context such as the authenticated principal, roles, permissions, or ownership.\n\nDo not treat a client-controlled cookie as the sole access-control mechanism, even if it is encrypted or signed. Use the framework's session management or token validation layer, avoid returning silent success values for denied access, and respond with explicit 401 or 403 errors. Centralize access-control rules so similar endpoints cannot be reached without the same checks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import abort, jsonify\nfrom flask_login import current_user, login_required\n\n@login_required\ndef load(request):\n    if not current_user.is_authenticated:\n        abort(401)\n\n    user_country = getcountry(request.remote_addr)\n    if current_user.country != user_country:\n        abort(403)\n\n    return jsonify({\n        'username': current_user.username,\n        'country': current_user.country,\n    })\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nflask\nflask-login\ncryptography\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-community/Broken_Access_Control)\n- [OWASP Authorization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authorization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-306: Missing Authentication for Critical Function](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html)\n- [CWE-862: Missing Authorization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html)\n- [Django authentication and authorization](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/stable/topics/auth/default/)\n- [Flask-Login documentation](https://flask-login.readthedocs.io/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-306",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-862",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-306",
                  "CWE-862"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "50d955cf-aed7-3643-802d-3b3c0af65a93",
              "name": "Raw Password Written To SQL Password Column",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is insecure password storage. In this Python code, the password value is written directly into the database instead of storing a derived password hash.\n\nStoring raw passwords creates immediate account compromise risk if the database is exposed, logged, or backed up insecurely. The sink shown also builds the SQL statement with string formatting, which allows attacker-controlled input such as username or password to alter the query.\n\nFix this by deriving a salted password hash with a password-specific algorithm before persistence, then store only the encoded hash string. In Python, use a well-known password hashing library such as bcrypt or Argon2, and execute the update with parameterized SQL so user input is never concatenated into the statement.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nNever store user passwords in plaintext or with fast general-purpose hashes such as MD5 or SHA-256 alone. Use a dedicated password hashing function with a per-password salt and a work factor designed for credential storage, such as bcrypt, Argon2id, or PBKDF2 with strong parameters.\n\nIn Python database code, always use parameterized queries provided by the DB-API driver instead of string formatting or concatenation. If your schema allows it, store the full encoded password hash produced by the library so verification can be performed later without keeping the original password.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport bcrypt\n\npassword_hash = bcrypt.hashpw(password.encode(\"utf-8\"), bcrypt.gensalt()).decode(\"utf-8\")\n\nc.execute(\n    \"UPDATE users SET password = ? WHERE username = ?\",\n    (password_hash, username),\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nbcrypt\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-256: Plaintext Storage of a Password](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html#hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-256",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-256",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "514a52f7-9e84-3b1e-be4a-b0519038bc0f",
              "name": "GET Route Performs State-Changing Action",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery through a state-changing GET route. In this Flask handler, a GET request to /disable disables MFA for the logged-in user, which changes server-side security state and can be triggered by a browser automatically through links, images, or other cross-site requests.\n\nState-changing actions should not be exposed over GET because GET is intended to be safe and idempotent. A malicious site could cause an authenticated user to load this endpoint and disable MFA without their intent. For this route, change the operation to POST and require CSRF validation before calling libmfa.mfa_disable(...).\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse POST, PUT, PATCH, or DELETE for operations that modify application state, and reserve GET for read-only requests. In Flask applications, enable CSRF protection globally for form submissions and validate a per-request token before performing the action. For sensitive actions such as disabling MFA, also consider requiring explicit user confirmation or recent re-authentication. Ensure session cookies are marked Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite where appropriate, but do not treat cookie settings as a replacement for CSRF tokens.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, redirect, request, url_for, abort, g\nfrom flask_wtf.csrf import CSRFProtect, validate_csrf\nfrom wtforms.validators import ValidationError\n\nmod_mfa = Blueprint('mod_mfa', __name__)\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\n\ndef init_app(app):\n    csrf.init_app(app)\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/disable', methods=['POST'])\ndef do_mfa_disable():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    token = request.form.get('csrf_token', '')\n    try:\n        validate_csrf(token)\n    except ValidationError:\n        abort(400)\n\n    libmfa.mfa_disable(g.session['username'])\n    return redirect('/mfa/')\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross Site Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "532f2b44-53c9-3901-8c49-60c70b2a79e0",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis route has a cross-site request forgery vulnerability. A state-changing Flask endpoint accepts POSTed form data and updates the authenticated session, but there is no visible CSRF token validation or request-origin verification.\n\nIn Flask, any POST handler that logs a user in, changes account state, or performs other sensitive actions should require a per-request or per-form CSRF token. Without that check, another site can cause a victim’s browser to submit a forged request with the victim’s cookies attached.\n\nFor the shown /create handler, enable framework-level CSRF protection and render the token in the HTML form. If this endpoint is intended to accept browser form submissions, use Flask-WTF CSRFProtect so POST requests are rejected unless they include a valid token tied to the user session. Origin or Referer validation can be added as a defense-in-depth check, but token validation should be the primary control.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nProtect all browser-accessible state-changing routes with CSRF validation, especially POST, PUT, PATCH, and DELETE handlers that rely on cookie-based authentication or sessions. In Flask applications, the standard fix is to enable Flask-WTF CSRFProtect globally so unsafe methods are checked consistently instead of relying on per-route custom logic.\n\nRender a CSRF token in every HTML form and reject requests with missing or invalid tokens. Keep SECRET_KEY strong and private because CSRF tokens depend on it. Also mark session cookies Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite=Lax or Strict where compatibility allows.\n\nUse Origin or Referer validation only as an additional safeguard, not as the sole control. If an endpoint is intended for API clients rather than browser forms, prefer explicit bearer-token authentication and avoid cookie-based ambient credentials.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, redirect, render_template, request, session\nfrom flask_wtf.csrf import CSRFProtect\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\nmod_user = Blueprint('user', __name__)\n\n@mod_user.route('/create', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_create():\n    session.pop('username', None)\n\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        username = request.form.get('username', '')\n        password = request.form.get('password', '')\n        email = request.form.get('email', '')\n\n        session['username'] = libuser.login(username, password)\n\n        if session['username']:\n            return redirect('/')\n\n    return render_template('user.create.html')\n\n# Application setup\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config['SECRET_KEY'] = 'replace-with-a-strong-random-secret'\ncsrf.init_app(app)\napp.register_blueprint(mod_user)\n\n# user.create.html template snippet\n<form method=\"post\" action=\"{{ url_for('user.do_create') }}\">\n  <input type=\"hidden\" name=\"csrf_token\" value=\"{{ csrf_token() }}\">\n  <input type=\"text\" name=\"username\">\n  <input type=\"password\" name=\"password\">\n  <input type=\"email\" name=\"email\">\n  <button type=\"submit\">Create</button>\n</form>\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "562777b9-358d-3dca-8b3f-f4d770c0ed21",
              "name": "SQL Injection Via Raw SQL Query Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in database query construction. This code builds an INSERT statement by interpolating Python values directly into the SQL string before calling execute(). If any inserted value is influenced by external input, an attacker can alter the SQL syntax, bypass intended logic, or write unexpected data to the database.\n\nIn Python, DB-API drivers expect parameterized queries where SQL and data are sent separately. For the sink shown here, the fix is to replace string formatting with placeholders and pass the values as a separate tuple or mapping. That ensures the driver treats username and the other fields as data, not executable SQL. If you are using SQLAlchemy, use bound parameters with text() or prefer the ORM/Core expression APIs instead of composing raw SQL strings.\n\nThis specific INSERT statement should not embed username with % formatting. Use the placeholder style required by the active driver, and keep static defaults as parameters too for consistency. This removes the injection path and avoids quoting bugs when values contain apostrophes or other special characters.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not construct SQL with string concatenation, percent formatting, f-strings, or format(). Use parameterized queries for every variable, even for numeric fields and default values. Keep SQL structure fixed and pass user-controlled values separately through the database driver.\n\nIf the project uses SQLAlchemy, prefer ORM inserts or sqlalchemy.text() with named bind parameters instead of raw string assembly. Also validate inputs at the application boundary, run database accounts with least privilege, and avoid exposing detailed database errors to users because they can help refine injection attempts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, salt, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\"\nc.execute(sql, (username, '', '', 0, 0, ''))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nsqlite3 (standard library)\nSQLAlchemy\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [SQLAlchemy text() and bound parameters](https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/20/core/sqlelement.html#sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "56417e01-a711-30b8-9ece-65c3abf2090a",
              "name": "Insecure Use Of App Run In Flask",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nImproper top-level startup of a development web server. In Python, calling Flask's app.run(...) at import time causes the server to start whenever the module is imported, which can lead to unintended execution during testing, tooling, multiprocessing, or production deployment. Flask also expects application startup to be guarded so imports remain side-effect free.\n\nIn this case, the application starts the built-in Flask development server with debug mode enabled and a fixed local bind address. Debug mode should not be enabled outside local development because it increases exposure of sensitive internals and changes runtime behavior. Move the startup behind a __main__ guard and keep debug disabled by default so the module can be safely imported by a real WSGI server or other application code.\n\nIf HTTPS is needed for local development, keeping ssl_context is acceptable, but the certificate and key paths should be sourced from controlled configuration rather than hard-coded in executable startup code. For production, run the Flask app under a supported WSGI server and terminate TLS with the deployment stack or server configuration instead of relying on app.run(...).\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nKeep Flask application modules import-safe by avoiding server startup at the top level. Put app.run(...) inside a main function and call it only under if __name__ == \"__main__\" so imports do not trigger side effects. Disable debug by default and enable it only through controlled development configuration.\n\nDo not use the built-in development server as the production entry point. Expose the Flask app object for a WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI, and handle TLS with the deployment environment. When local TLS is required, load certificate paths from environment variables or other trusted configuration instead of embedding file paths directly in code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Flask\nimport os\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\n\ndef main() -> None:\n    debug = os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\"\n    cert_path = os.getenv(\"FLASK_CERT_PATH\")\n    key_path = os.getenv(\"FLASK_KEY_PATH\")\n    ssl_context = (cert_path, key_path) if cert_path and key_path else None\n\n    app.run(\n        debug=debug,\n        host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n        ssl_context=ssl_context,\n    )\n\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nflask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Development Server](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/server/)\n- [Python __main__ — Top-level code environment](https://docs.python.org/3/library/__main__.html)\n- [Deploying to Production](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/deploying/)\n- [Werkzeug Serving](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/serving/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-668",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/668.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-668"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "626f0446-109a-3f86-bd97-2ab5fe7e40f3",
              "name": "SQL Injection Via Raw SQL Query Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection is present where untrusted input is concatenated into a database query. In Python, building SQL with string formatting allows attacker-controlled values such as username or password to change the meaning of the statement instead of being treated strictly as data.\n\nIn the shown sink, both values are inserted directly into the SELECT statement with .format(...). An attacker can supply crafted input that bypasses authentication, reads unintended rows, or alters query behavior. The fix is to use parameterized queries so the database driver binds values separately from the SQL text.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not build SQL statements with string concatenation, f-strings, percent formatting, or str.format when any part comes from users or external systems. Use the database driver's parameter binding API for all variable values. For Python DB-API clients such as sqlite3, pass placeholders in the SQL and provide parameters as a separate tuple or mapping.\n\nPrefer higher-level query builders or ORM APIs when possible, because they make safe parameter binding the default. Keep dynamic SQL limited to trusted structural elements such as fixed column lists, and if query structure must vary, select from an allowlist rather than inserting raw input into the statement. Also avoid storing plain-text passwords; store salted password hashes and verify them with a dedicated password-hashing library.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nuser = c.execute(\n    \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = ? AND password = ?\",\n    (username, password),\n).fetchone()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nsqlite3\nbcrypt\nSQLAlchemy>=2.0\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [SQLAlchemy textual SQL with bound parameters](https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/20/core/sqlelement.html#sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "638bd8d0-7bff-312b-9a8b-43382c87476e",
              "name": "Raw Password Written To SQL Password Column",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nPlaintext password storage. This code inserts the value from `password` directly into the database, which exposes user credentials if the database, logs, backups, or administrative tooling are accessed by an attacker.\n\nIn Python, passwords should be transformed with a slow, salted password hashing function before persistence, and the database should store only the derived hash. The shown sink also builds SQL with string interpolation, so the fix should replace direct formatting with a parameterized query while storing a password hash instead of the raw secret.\n\nUse a dedicated password hashing algorithm such as PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA256, bcrypt, scrypt, or Argon2. Generate a unique random salt per password, encode the result in a stable storage format, and verify later by recomputing the hash with the stored parameters rather than decrypting anything.\n\nThis change limits credential exposure and also hardens the database write path against injection by binding parameters separately from SQL text.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nNever store user passwords in plaintext or in a reversible form. Store only a salted password hash produced by a password-specific algorithm with work factors that can be increased over time. In Python, PBKDF2-HMAC from the standard library is acceptable; Argon2, scrypt, or bcrypt are also appropriate when available.\n\nDo not build SQL statements with string formatting when writing credential data. Use parameterized queries so user-controlled values are bound safely, and keep password hashing in a dedicated function that produces a self-describing stored format including algorithm, salt, and cost. When users authenticate, verify with constant-time comparison and upgrade older hashes during login if policy changes.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport base64\nimport hashlib\nimport hmac\nimport os\nimport sqlite3\n\n\ndef hash_password(password: str) -> str:\n    salt = os.urandom(16)\n    iterations = 600_000\n    derived_key = hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac(\n        \"sha256\",\n        password.encode(\"utf-8\"),\n        salt,\n        iterations,\n    )\n    return \"pbkdf2_sha256${}${}${}\".format(\n        iterations,\n        base64.b64encode(salt).decode(\"ascii\"),\n        base64.b64encode(derived_key).decode(\"ascii\"),\n    )\n\n\ndef verify_password(password: str, stored_value: str) -> bool:\n    algorithm, iterations_text, salt_b64, hash_b64 = stored_value.split(\"$\", 3)\n    if algorithm != \"pbkdf2_sha256\":\n        return False\n\n    derived_key = hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac(\n        \"sha256\",\n        password.encode(\"utf-8\"),\n        base64.b64decode(salt_b64),\n        int(iterations_text),\n    )\n    return hmac.compare_digest(\n        derived_key,\n        base64.b64decode(hash_b64),\n    )\n\n\npassword_hash = hash_password(password)\nc.execute(\n    \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\",\n    (username, password_hash, 0, 0, \"\"),\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport base64\nimport hashlib\nimport hmac\nimport os\nimport sqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-256: Plaintext Storage of a Password](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html)\n- [Python hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html#hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-256",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-256"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6953c875-f699-37f4-9ba2-645b11f43234",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Writing sensitive data to a predictable path under /tmp in Python can expose the file to tampering, disclosure, or race-condition attacks because other local users or processes may pre-create, replace, or read that path depending on system permissions and symlink behavior.\n\nIn this case, opening '/tmp/acme.key' directly is unsafe for key material because the filename is fixed and the directory is shared. Use Python's tempfile facilities to create a unique file securely with restricted permissions, and prefer a private directory when storing secrets. If the data must persist, create the file atomically and set the mode so only the current account can read and write it.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not construct temporary file paths manually in shared locations such as /tmp when the content is sensitive. Use tempfile.mkstemp(), NamedTemporaryFile(), or TemporaryDirectory() so the runtime creates a unique path atomically. Restrict permissions to the owner, avoid following attacker-controlled paths, and remove the file as soon as it is no longer needed. For persistent secret material, prefer an application-owned directory with 0700 permissions instead of a world-writable temp directory.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"acme_\", suffix=\".key\")\ntry:\n    os.fchmod(fd, 0o600)\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as out:\n        out.write(key_bytes)\nfinally:\n    pass\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6be2be1b-b54d-3d5e-8c29-ee3b3683a916",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. This code starts a Python web application with TLS material loaded from files under /tmp, which is a shared temporary directory on Unix-like systems. Certificate and private key files stored there can be replaced, read, or linked by other local users or processes if file creation and permissions are not tightly controlled.\n\nIn this sink, ssl_context points to /tmp/acme.cert and /tmp/acme.key while the application is also running in debug mode. A private key should be kept in a dedicated protected location with restrictive permissions, not in a world-writable temporary path. Move the certificate and key to an application-controlled directory, ensure the key file is readable only by the service account, and disable debug mode outside local development.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not store certificate or private key files in shared temporary directories such as /tmp. Keep TLS assets in a dedicated directory owned by the application or service account, set the private key permissions to owner-read only, and verify the path is not a symlink before loading it. In Python, prefer pathlib and os.stat or os.open-based checks to enforce expected ownership and mode before use.\n\nDo not use the built-in debug server for deployed environments. Run the application behind a production WSGI server and terminate TLS with properly managed certificates, or load certificates from a protected secrets or configuration location. If temporary files are genuinely required elsewhere in the application, create them with Python's tempfile APIs so they are created securely with restrictive permissions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nBASE_DIR = Path(\"/etc/myapp/tls\")\nCERT_FILE = BASE_DIR / \"acme.cert\"\nKEY_FILE = BASE_DIR / \"acme.key\"\n\nkey_stat = os.stat(KEY_FILE)\nif key_stat.st_mode & 0o077:\n    raise PermissionError(\"TLS private key permissions must be 600 or stricter\")\n\napp.run(\n    debug=False,\n    host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n    ssl_context=(str(CERT_FILE), str(KEY_FILE)),\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nflask\nwerkzeug\npython >=3.8\nopenssl (system package for certificate management)\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Flask Development Server Documentation](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/server/)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6be401d7-3597-35f4-a23f-3cf6e295192f",
              "name": "Flask App Running In Debug Mode",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an enabled debug mode vulnerability. In a Python Flask application, starting the server with debug mode turned on exposes detailed error pages and an interactive debugger that is intended only for local development.\n\nIn the shown sink, app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', port=5000, extra_files='csp.txt') explicitly enables Flask and Werkzeug debugging features. If this setting is used outside a strictly controlled development environment, an attacker who can reach the service may obtain stack traces, sensitive configuration details, and potentially interactive code execution through the debugger. The fix is to disable debug mode in code and rely on environment-specific configuration so development and production settings are separated.\n\nFor Flask applications, do not hardcode debug=True in the run call. Default to debug disabled, avoid using the built-in development server for deployment, and run the application behind a production WSGI server with debug features turned off.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDisable Flask debug mode by default and never enable it in deployed environments. Remove hardcoded debug=True values from app.run calls, and gate any development-only behavior behind environment variables with a safe default of disabled.\n\nUse Flask debug mode only during local development, and do not expose the development server to untrusted networks. For production, run the application with a production-grade WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI, keep FLASK_DEBUG unset or set to 0, and ensure exception details are logged server-side rather than returned to clients.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    debug = os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\"\n    app.run(\n        debug=debug,\n        host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n        port=5000,\n        extra_files=[\"csp.txt\"] if debug else None,\n    )\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debug Mode](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Werkzeug Documentation: Debugging Applications](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debug/)\n- [Flask Documentation: Deploying to Production](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/deploying/)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6ed74063-0b6a-3c5b-8c43-7aed4374390b",
              "name": "SQL Injection Via Raw SQL Query Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in a database update query. The code builds an UPDATE statement by formatting untrusted values directly into the SQL string, which lets crafted input change the query structure instead of being treated strictly as data.\n\nIn Python, DB-API drivers such as sqlite3 support parameterized queries and will bind values safely when placeholders are used. For this sink, replace string formatting with query parameters so the password and username are sent separately from the SQL text. If this code uses SQLAlchemy, use bound parameters with text() or prefer the ORM or expression language for updates.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not compose SQL with format(), f-strings, percent formatting, or string concatenation when any part of the statement depends on external input. Use parameterized queries provided by the Python DB-API, and keep SQL text static while passing user-controlled values as a separate tuple or mapping.\n\nFor sqlite3, use ? placeholders. For other Python drivers, use that driver's supported parameter style, such as %s or named parameters. If the project uses SQLAlchemy, use text(\"UPDATE users SET password = :password WHERE username = :username\") with a parameter dictionary, or use SQLAlchemy Core or ORM update APIs. Also validate business inputs, restrict database account permissions, and store passwords with a strong password hashing function rather than writing plaintext passwords to the database.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"UPDATE users SET password = ? WHERE username = ?\"\nc.execute(sql, (password, username))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport sqlite3\nfrom sqlalchemy import text\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [SQLAlchemy textual SQL with bound parameters](https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/20/core/sqlelement.html#sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
