            {
              "id": "6fb1b190-c108-3417-a082-3b3bc36e91b2",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery in a state-changing Flask route. This POST endpoint enables MFA for the currently authenticated session and reads user-supplied form data, but there is no visible CSRF validation before the account state is changed.\n\nIn Flask applications that rely on session cookies, the browser will automatically attach those cookies to cross-site requests unless additional protections are enforced. That allows an attacker to cause a victim's browser to submit a forged POST to this route. Even though the route verifies an OTP, the request should still be bound to a trusted form submission from your application by validating a CSRF token and rejecting requests with an unexpected Origin or Referer.\n\nFor this handler, add route or application-level CSRF protection and include a CSRF token in the MFA enable form. As a defense in depth measure, verify that unsafe requests originate from your own site, and keep session cookies configured with Secure, HttpOnly, and an appropriate SameSite policy.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse framework-backed CSRF protection for every state-changing Flask route that accepts cookie-authenticated requests. In practice, enable CSRFProtect at the application layer or use FlaskForm with validate_on_submit() so the token is generated server-side, embedded in the form, and verified on POST before any account change occurs.\n\nFor sensitive actions such as enabling MFA, add a same-origin check on unsafe methods by validating the Origin header when present and falling back to Referer validation when needed. Also configure the session cookie with SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE = True, SESSION_COOKIE_HTTPONLY = True, and a restrictive SESSION_COOKIE_SAMESITE value so the browser is less likely to send authenticated cookies in cross-site contexts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Flask, abort, flash, g, redirect, render_template, request, url_for\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import StringField, SubmitField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired\nimport pyotp\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config['SECRET_KEY'] = 'change-this-secret-key'\napp.config['WTF_CSRF_TIME_LIMIT'] = 3600\ncsrf = CSRFProtect(app)\n\nclass MFAEnableForm(FlaskForm):\n    otp = StringField('OTP', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    submit = SubmitField('Enable MFA')\n\n\ndef _same_origin_required():\n    origin = request.headers.get('Origin')\n    host_url = request.host_url.rstrip('/')\n    if origin and origin.rstrip('/') != host_url:\n        abort(403)\n\n    referer = request.headers.get('Referer')\n    if not origin and referer and not referer.startswith(request.host_url):\n        abort(403)\n\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_mfa_enable():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    form = MFAEnableForm()\n\n    if form.validate_on_submit():\n        _same_origin_required()\n\n        secret = libmfa.mfa_get_secret(g.session['username'])\n        totp = pyotp.TOTP(secret)\n\n        if totp.verify(form.otp.data):\n            libmfa.mfa_enable(g.session['username'])\n            return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n        flash('The OTP was incorrect')\n        return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n    return render_template('mfa.enable.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\nFlask\npyotp\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Security Considerations](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/web-security/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "72bf6ac1-3fc1-3f8e-b996-1353c6a2ec61",
              "name": "SQL Injection Via Raw SQL Query Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in database query construction. This code builds an INSERT statement with Python string interpolation and sends the resulting SQL directly to the database. If any value such as the username or password contains SQL control characters, an attacker can alter the query structure, insert unintended data, or trigger errors that expose database behavior.\n\nIn Python, DB-API drivers are designed to separate SQL text from data values through parameterized queries. For the sink shown here, the fix is to keep the SQL statement static and pass user-controlled values as parameters to execute(). The driver will bind and escape them correctly for the target database instead of treating them as executable SQL.\n\nIf this code uses sqlite3, use ? placeholders. If the project uses SQLAlchemy for raw SQL, use text() with named parameters, or prefer the ORM/Core expression APIs for inserts. Avoid manual quoting, %-formatting, f-strings, and .format() when composing SQL with runtime values.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized queries for all database reads and writes, including INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, and SELECT. Keep the SQL statement constant and pass untrusted input through the driver parameter API rather than concatenating or interpolating values into the query string.\n\nAlso enforce server-side input validation, least-privilege database accounts, and consistent error handling that does not expose SQL details. When query structure must be dynamic, build it from allowlisted column names or use SQLAlchemy Core or ORM constructs instead of raw string assembly.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\"\nc.execute(sql, (u, p, 0, 0, ''))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nsqlite3 (Python standard library)\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [SQLAlchemy Textual SQL with bound parameters](https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/20/core/sqlelement.html#sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "73a16a25-e6c0-37c7-9a46-cc7082a66055",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. In Python, opening a fixed path under /tmp such as /tmp/ca.key is unsafe because that directory is shared by other local users and processes. An attacker can pre-create the file, replace it with a symlink, or read sensitive material if permissions are too broad.\n\nFor a key file, this is especially risky because private key material must only be readable by the intended process. Instead of reading from a predictable filename in /tmp, create the file in a secure way with restrictive permissions and use the returned path or file handle. If the file already exists only for the current process, place it in a directory with controlled permissions or use Python's tempfile APIs to manage it securely.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use predictable names in shared temporary directories for sensitive files. Use tempfile.mkstemp(), NamedTemporaryFile(), or TemporaryDirectory() so the file is created atomically. Restrict permissions to owner-only access, avoid following attacker-controlled paths, and delete the file as soon as it is no longer needed. For cryptographic keys, prefer keeping the material in memory when possible instead of writing it to disk at all.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, key_path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"ca_\", suffix=\".key\")\ntry:\n    os.fchmod(fd, 0o600)\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as key_file:\n        key_file.write(private_key_bytes)\n\n    with open(key_path, \"rb\") as key_file:\n        key_data = key_file.read()\nfinally:\n    if os.path.exists(key_path):\n        os.remove(key_path)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ntempfile\nos\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7827c316-f7c9-3d69-b744-52ea64deaa28",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Reading sensitive material from a fixed path under /tmp is unsafe in Python because that directory is typically shared by multiple users and processes, and predictable names such as /tmp/acme.key are vulnerable to symlink attacks, file replacement, race conditions, and unintended disclosure.\n\nIn this sink, the code opens a key file from a world-writable temporary location using a hard-coded filename. An attacker who can write to /tmp may create or replace that path before it is opened, causing the application to read attacker-controlled content or expose secret key material. Mitigate this by storing key files outside shared temporary directories, creating them with restrictive permissions, and validating that the path refers to the expected regular file before use.\n\nIf temporary storage is required, use Python's tempfile APIs to create a unique file or directory securely, restrict permissions to the current user, and avoid predictable names. For long-lived keys, prefer an application-controlled directory such as one under the user's home directory or a protected service-specific data directory instead of /tmp.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not place secrets or trust-sensitive files at predictable names in shared temporary directories such as /tmp. Use a protected application directory with owner-only permissions for persistent keys. When temporary files are necessary, create them with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile, tempfile.mkstemp, or tempfile.TemporaryDirectory so the name is unique and creation is atomic.\n\nBefore opening an existing key file, verify that it is a regular file, not a symlink, and that its permissions do not allow group or world access. Keep the file outside publicly writable locations, ensure the parent directory is also restricted, and avoid following user-controlled paths for security-sensitive reads.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nimport stat\n\nkey_path = Path.home() / \".acme\" / \"acme.key\"\nkey_path.parent.mkdir(mode=0o700, parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n\nfile_stat = key_path.stat()\nif not stat.S_ISREG(file_stat.st_mode):\n    raise ValueError(\"Key path must be a regular file\")\nif file_stat.st_mode & 0o077:\n    raise PermissionError(\"Key file permissions must be restricted to the owner\")\n\nwith key_path.open(\"rb\") as key_file:\n    key_data = key_file.read()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nimport stat\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [Python pathlib — Object-oriented filesystem paths](https://docs.python.org/3/library/pathlib.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "794cfa23-3b60-3d9c-b64d-8e3affa05713",
              "name": "Login Route Lacks Rate Limiting And Throttling",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis route has insufficient protection against brute-force authentication attempts. The Flask login handler accepts repeated username, password, and OTP submissions, but it does not apply rate limits, track failed attempts, or impose temporary lockouts before creating a session.\n\nIn Python web applications, an unthrottled login endpoint allows attackers to automate password guessing and OTP guessing at high speed. In the code shown, both the primary password check and the MFA validation can be retried without delay, which increases the chance of account compromise and can also enable account enumeration and denial of service against targeted users.\n\nProtect this endpoint by enforcing request throttling and per-account failure bookkeeping. Apply a rate limit to the route, maintain server-side counters for failed password and MFA attempts, and temporarily block authentication for a username after too many failures. Reset the counters after a successful login and return the same generic error message for all authentication failures.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse layered controls on authentication endpoints: a per-IP rate limit, a per-account failure counter, and a temporary lockout or exponential backoff after repeated failures. Store counters in a shared server-side store such as Redis or the application database so protection works across multiple workers and application instances.\n\nApply the same generic failure response for unknown users, bad passwords, and invalid OTP values to avoid leaking which factor failed. Reset failure counters only after the full authentication flow succeeds, including MFA. If the application is behind a reverse proxy, configure trusted proxy handling correctly before using client IP addresses for throttling decisions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, flash, make_response, redirect, render_template, request\nfrom flask_limiter import Limiter\nfrom flask_limiter.util import get_remote_address\nimport time\n\nmod_user = Blueprint('mod_user', __name__)\nlimiter = Limiter(key_func=get_remote_address)\n\n_FAILED_LOGINS = {}\n_MAX_ATTEMPTS = 5\n_LOCKOUT_SECONDS = 900\n\n\ndef _client_ip():\n    forwarded_for = request.headers.get('X-Forwarded-For', '')\n    if forwarded_for:\n        return forwarded_for.split(',')[0].strip()\n    return request.remote_addr or 'unknown'\n\n\ndef _failure_key(username):\n    return (username or '').strip().lower(), _client_ip()\n\n\ndef _is_locked(username):\n    key = _failure_key(username)\n    record = _FAILED_LOGINS.get(key)\n    if not record:\n        return False\n    if record['count'] < _MAX_ATTEMPTS:\n        return False\n    if time.time() >= record['locked_until']:\n        _FAILED_LOGINS.pop(key, None)\n        return False\n    return True\n\n\ndef _record_failure(username):\n    key = _failure_key(username)\n    now = time.time()\n    record = _FAILED_LOGINS.get(key, {'count': 0, 'locked_until': 0})\n\n    if now >= record['locked_until']:\n        record['locked_until'] = 0\n\n    record['count'] += 1\n    if record['count'] >= _MAX_ATTEMPTS:\n        record['locked_until'] = now + _LOCKOUT_SECONDS\n\n    _FAILED_LOGINS[key] = record\n\n\ndef _clear_failures(username):\n    _FAILED_LOGINS.pop(_failure_key(username), None)\n\n\n@mod_user.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\n@limiter.limit('10 per minute')\ndef do_login():\n    session.pop('username', None)\n\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        submitted_username = (request.form.get('username') or '').strip()\n        password = request.form.get('password') or ''\n        otp = request.form.get('otp') or ''\n\n        if _is_locked(submitted_username):\n            flash('Invalid credentials')\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 429\n\n        authenticated_username = libuser.login(submitted_username, password)\n        if not authenticated_username:\n            _record_failure(submitted_username)\n            flash('Invalid credentials')\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 401\n\n        if libmfa.mfa_is_enabled(authenticated_username):\n            if not libmfa.mfa_validate(authenticated_username, otp):\n                _record_failure(authenticated_username)\n                flash('Invalid credentials')\n                return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 401\n\n        _clear_failures(authenticated_username)\n        response = make_response(redirect('/'))\n        response = libsession.create(request=request, response=response, username=authenticated_username)\n        return response\n\n    return render_template('user.login.mfa.html')\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-Limiter\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Blocking Brute Force Attacks](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/Blocking_Brute_Force_Attacks)\n- [OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authentication_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-307: Improper Restriction of Excessive Authentication Attempts](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/307.html)\n- [Flask-Limiter Documentation](https://flask-limiter.readthedocs.io/en/stable/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-307",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/307.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-307"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7cdc69ca-991c-3b0f-bb16-422d8d8bbbb0",
              "name": "Hardcoded Fernet Key In Source Code",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded cryptographic key. In this Python code, the Fernet secret is embedded directly in source as a string literal and then passed to Fernet(key). Any developer, contractor, attacker with repository access, or user who can read deployed artifacts can recover that key and decrypt protected data or forge valid ciphertexts.\n\nFor Fernet in Python, the key should be provided at runtime from a protected configuration source such as an environment variable or a dedicated secret manager, not committed to the repository. Because the current key is already exposed in code history, treat it as compromised: replace it, remove it from source, and rotate any encrypted data or tokens that depend on it according to your application's key management process.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nGenerate Fernet keys with Fernet.generate_key() and store them outside the codebase in environment configuration or a managed secret store. Restrict access to the secret to only the running service account, and never log or print the key. Since the exposed key has been committed, rotate it immediately, remove it from version control history where appropriate, and re-encrypt sensitive data or invalidate tokens created with the old key if your application requires that assurance. Add secret-scanning and code review checks to prevent new hardcoded keys from being introduced.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom cryptography.fernet import Fernet\n\nkey = os.environ[\"FERNET_KEY\"].encode(\"ascii\")\nfernet = Fernet(key)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ncryptography\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)\n- [OWASP Secrets Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Secrets_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [cryptography.io: Fernet (symmetric encryption)](https://cryptography.io/en/latest/fernet/)\n- [Python os module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "81a7fab8-2fda-3dbf-956f-9c5f06bac559",
              "name": "Hardcoded Configuration Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded secret in application configuration. In Python web applications, embedding a Flask SECRET_KEY directly in source code exposes a sensitive value to anyone who can read the repository, logs, backups, or deployed artifacts. If that key is reused across environments or leaked, attackers can tamper with signed session data and other security-sensitive application features that depend on the secret.\n\nFor the shown sink, assigning app.config['SECRET_KEY'] to a literal string should be replaced with loading the secret from the environment or a protected configuration source at runtime. This keeps the key out of version control and allows separate secrets per environment. The application should also fail fast if the variable is missing, rather than silently using an insecure default.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nStore secrets outside the codebase and inject them at deployment time using environment variables, a secrets manager, or protected instance configuration. Use a strong randomly generated value for each environment, rotate it if exposure is suspected, and never commit sample production secrets to source control. In Flask, load the secret during startup and raise an error when it is absent so the application cannot run with an unsafe fallback.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\nsecret_key = os.environ[\"SECRET_KEY\"]\napp.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"] = secret_key\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Use of Hard-coded Password](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)\n- [Flask Documentation: Configuration Handling](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#configuration-basics)\n- [Python Documentation: os.environ](https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "83a73e6d-d0b3-3b7e-a63b-b13449d67123",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Reading sensitive material from a fixed path under /tmp is unsafe in Python because that directory is typically shared by multiple users and processes, and predictable names such as /tmp/acme.key are vulnerable to symlink attacks, file replacement, race conditions, and unintended disclosure.\n\nIn this sink, the code opens a key file from a world-writable temporary location using a hard-coded filename. An attacker who can write to /tmp may create or replace that path before it is opened, causing the application to read attacker-controlled content or expose secret key material. Mitigate this by storing key files outside shared temporary directories, creating them with restrictive permissions, and validating that the path refers to the expected regular file before use.\n\nIf temporary storage is required, use Python's tempfile APIs to create a unique file or directory securely, restrict permissions to the current user, and avoid predictable names. For long-lived keys, prefer an application-controlled directory such as one under the user's home directory or a protected service-specific data directory instead of /tmp.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not place secrets or trust-sensitive files at predictable names in shared temporary directories such as /tmp. Use a protected application directory with owner-only permissions for persistent keys. When temporary files are necessary, create them with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile, tempfile.mkstemp, or tempfile.TemporaryDirectory so the name is unique and creation is atomic.\n\nBefore opening an existing key file, verify that it is a regular file, not a symlink, and that its permissions do not allow group or world access. Keep the file outside publicly writable locations, ensure the parent directory is also restricted, and avoid following user-controlled paths for security-sensitive reads.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nimport stat\n\nkey_path = Path.home() / \".acme\" / \"acme.key\"\nkey_path.parent.mkdir(mode=0o700, parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n\nfile_stat = key_path.stat()\nif not stat.S_ISREG(file_stat.st_mode):\n    raise ValueError(\"Key path must be a regular file\")\nif file_stat.st_mode & 0o077:\n    raise PermissionError(\"Key file permissions must be restricted to the owner\")\n\nwith key_path.open(\"rb\") as key_file:\n    key_data = key_file.read()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nimport stat\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [Python pathlib — Object-oriented filesystem paths](https://docs.python.org/3/library/pathlib.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8b3b4581-006b-313f-8af7-a1b7bc3a847d",
              "name": "GET Route Performs State-Changing Action",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery in a state-changing route. This Flask handler disables MFA through a GET endpoint, which makes a security-sensitive action triggerable by simply loading a URL. Browsers automatically send cookies and other ambient credentials on cross-site requests, so an attacker can cause a logged-in user to disable MFA without their intent.\n\nThe current referer check is not a sufficient defense. Referer headers can be absent, altered by privacy controls, or handled inconsistently across clients and proxies. In Python web applications built with Flask, state-changing operations such as disabling MFA should use POST and be protected with a per-request CSRF token validated server-side before the action is performed.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use GET for any action that changes account state, especially authentication settings such as enabling or disabling MFA. Reserve GET for safe, read-only operations and require POST for state changes so browsers, caches, crawlers, and prefetchers do not trigger the action accidentally.\n\nAdd CSRF protection using Flask-WTF or equivalent server-side token validation tied to the user session. Remove reliance on Referer as the primary control. For sensitive actions, also require the user to confirm intent with a form submission and consider step-up verification such as password re-entry or MFA confirmation before disabling MFA.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, redirect, g, request, abort, render_template\nfrom flask_wtf import CSRFProtect\nfrom flask_wtf.csrf import validate_csrf\nfrom wtforms import Form\n\nmod_mfa = Blueprint('mod_mfa', __name__)\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\n\nclass EmptyForm(Form):\n    pass\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/disable', methods=['POST'])\ndef do_mfa_disable():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    token = request.form.get('csrf_token', '')\n    try:\n        validate_csrf(token)\n    except Exception:\n        abort(400)\n\n    libmfa.mfa_disable(g.session['username'])\n    return redirect('/mfa/')\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/disable', methods=['GET'])\ndef disable_mfa_confirm():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    form = EmptyForm()\n    return render_template('mfa_disable_confirm.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "90b2d4ab-dc36-321e-bba5-f5350547cbcf",
              "name": "Hardcoded Configuration Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded secret in application configuration. In Python web applications, embedding a Flask SECRET_KEY directly in source code exposes a sensitive value to anyone who can read the repository, logs, backups, or deployed artifacts. If that key is reused across environments or leaked, attackers can tamper with signed session data and other security-sensitive application features that depend on the secret.\n\nFor the shown sink, assigning app.config['SECRET_KEY'] to a literal string should be replaced with loading the secret from the environment or a protected configuration source at runtime. This keeps the key out of version control and allows separate secrets per environment. The application should also fail fast if the variable is missing, rather than silently using an insecure default.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nStore secrets outside the codebase and inject them at deployment time using environment variables, a secrets manager, or protected instance configuration. Use a strong randomly generated value for each environment, rotate it if exposure is suspected, and never commit sample production secrets to source control. In Flask, load the secret during startup and raise an error when it is absent so the application cannot run with an unsafe fallback.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\nsecret_key = os.environ[\"SECRET_KEY\"]\napp.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"] = secret_key\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Use of Hard-coded Password](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)\n- [Flask Documentation: Configuration Handling](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#configuration-basics)\n- [Python Documentation: os.environ](https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "9181c227-499c-30af-bf94-5d24533def32",
              "name": "Missing Function Level Access Control",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is a missing function-level access control issue. The `create` view performs a security-sensitive action by creating a session cookie from user identity data, but it has no authentication or authorization check before doing so.\n\nIn Python web applications, a view like this must verify that the caller is authenticated and allowed to create or refresh a session for the specified user. As written, an unauthenticated request could reach the function and receive a valid encrypted cookie containing `username` and `country`. Encrypting the cookie value does not enforce access control; it only hides the contents.\n\nRestrict this endpoint with authentication and explicit authorization, and avoid trusting a route parameter for identity when the authenticated session already provides it. Build the cookie from the authenticated user instead of a caller-supplied username, and reject requests from users who are not permitted to perform this action.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nProtect every state-changing or identity-related view with framework authentication controls and an authorization check that runs on every request. Do not expose endpoints that mint session or identity cookies to anonymous users. Use the authenticated principal from the framework context instead of trusting a username passed in the URL, form data, or function arguments.\n\nApply deny-by-default authorization rules, return 401 for unauthenticated callers and 403 for authenticated callers without permission, and keep authorization logic close to the protected action. When issuing cookies, also set `HttpOnly`, `Secure`, and an appropriate `SameSite` value to reduce session theft and cross-site request risks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import abort, request\nfrom flask_login import current_user, login_required\n\n@login_required\ndef create(request, response, username):\n    if not current_user.is_authenticated:\n        abort(401)\n\n    if current_user.id != username and not getattr(current_user, \"is_admin\", False):\n        abort(403)\n\n    country = getcountry(request)\n    session_value = f\"{current_user.id}|{country}\".encode()\n    token = fernet.encrypt(session_value).decode()\n\n    response.set_cookie(\n        \"vulpy_session\",\n        token,\n        httponly=True,\n        secure=True,\n        samesite=\"Lax\"\n    )\n\n    return response\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nflask-login\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-community/Broken_Access_Control)\n- [OWASP Authorization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authorization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-306: Missing Authentication for Critical Function](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html)\n- [CWE-862: Missing Authorization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html)\n- [Django authentication and authorization](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/stable/topics/auth/default/)\n- [Flask-Login documentation](https://flask-login.readthedocs.io/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-306",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-862",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-306",
                  "CWE-862"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "953c557f-06d2-3b3a-bc7a-efee7e771c09",
              "name": "GET Route Performs State-Changing Action",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is a state-changing action exposed through a GET request, which creates a cross-site request forgery risk. In this Flask view, visiting the route can reset the user's MFA secret by calling libmfa.mfa_reset_secret, even though GET should be safe and not modify server-side state.\n\nBecause browsers automatically issue GET requests for links, images, and embedded content, an attacker can cause a logged-in user to trigger this endpoint without intending to. For this route, the fix is to separate display from mutation: keep GET for rendering the page, and move MFA secret reset or enable actions to a POST-only endpoint protected with a CSRF token.\n\nIn Python Flask applications, CSRF protection is commonly enforced with Flask-WTF. The handler should render the MFA setup page on GET, then accept a POST from a form that includes a CSRF token before resetting the secret and generating the provisioning QR code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not perform account changes, token rotation, secret generation, deletion, or any other server-side mutation in a GET handler. Reserve GET for safe reads and require POST, PUT, PATCH, or DELETE for actions that change state.\n\nEnable CSRF protection for all state-changing routes and validate a per-request token bound to the user session. In Flask, initialize CSRF protection centrally and ensure forms that trigger MFA enrollment, reset, disablement, or recovery submit via POST with a validated token. As an additional defense, avoid making sensitive actions happen automatically on page load and consider re-authentication for MFA reset flows.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom io import BytesIO\nimport base64\n\nimport pyotp\nimport qrcode\nfrom flask import Blueprint, g, redirect, render_template, request\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import SubmitField\n\nmod_mfa = Blueprint('mod_mfa', __name__)\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\n\n\nclass ResetMFAForm(FlaskForm):\n    submit = SubmitField('Generate new MFA secret')\n\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_mfa_view():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    username = g.session['username']\n    form = ResetMFAForm()\n\n    if libmfa.mfa_is_enabled(username):\n        return render_template('mfa.disable.html', form=form)\n\n    if request.method == 'POST' and form.validate_on_submit():\n        libmfa.mfa_reset_secret(username)\n        secret = libmfa.mfa_get_secret(username)\n        secret_url = pyotp.totp.TOTP(secret).provisioning_uri(username, issuer_name='Vulpy')\n        img = qrcode.make(secret_url)\n\n        buffered = BytesIO()\n        img.save(buffered, format='PNG')\n        img_str = base64.b64encode(buffered.getvalue()).decode()\n\n        return render_template('mfa.enable.html', form=form, secret_url=secret_url, img_str=img_str)\n\n    return render_template('mfa.enable.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "9570e00d-0035-3b09-8312-7e17e3fcd118",
              "name": "SQL Injection Via Raw SQL Query Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in Python database code occurs when untrusted values are interpolated directly into an SQL statement before execution. In the shown sink, user-controlled values are merged into an INSERT query with string formatting, so special characters can change the intended SQL structure or break query parsing.\n\nIn Python DB-API code, the correct fix is to keep SQL text static and pass data separately as bound parameters. The database driver then escapes and binds the values according to the protocol instead of treating them as executable SQL. For this INSERT statement, replace percent-formatting with parameter placeholders and provide the values as a separate tuple.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not build SQL by concatenation, interpolation, f-strings, or percent-formatting when any part of the data can come from outside the program. Use the parameter style supported by the Python database driver and pass values separately to execute(). Keep identifiers such as table names and column names fixed in code; if they must vary, select them from a strict allowlist rather than from raw input. Prefer higher-level query builders or ORM APIs when possible, and apply least-privilege database accounts so that a successful injection has limited impact.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"INSERT INTO users (user, password, failures) VALUES (?, ?, ?)\"\nc.execute(sql, (u, p, 0))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nsqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "960362af-7745-36a2-942b-9c0bc202e939",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Writing sensitive data directly to a predictable path such as /tmp/ca.key in Python is unsafe because temporary directories are typically shared across users and processes, and the filename can be guessed in advance.\n\nAn attacker on the same system can pre-create the file, replace it with a symlink, or race the application into writing private key material to an unintended location. In this case, the sink writes a certificate authority key, which is especially sensitive and should only be created with restrictive permissions and an unpredictable filename.\n\nUse Python's tempfile facilities or securely create the file with exclusive creation semantics and mode 0o600 so that only the current user can read and write it. If a fixed path is truly required, create it with os.open using O_CREAT | O_EXCL and a restrictive mode, then wrap the file descriptor with os.fdopen before writing.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not place sensitive files at predictable names under shared temporary directories. Generate temporary files with tempfile.mkstemp or tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile so the name is unpredictable and creation is atomic. When storing secrets such as private keys, ensure permissions are restricted to the owning user with mode 0o600. If the application must write to a specific location, create the file with os.open using O_CREAT, O_EXCL, and a restrictive mode to prevent overwrite and symlink attacks, then validate ownership and directory permissions before use.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"ca-\", suffix=\".key\")\ntry:\n    os.fchmod(fd, 0o600)\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as out:\n        out.write(key_bytes)\nfinally:\n    pass\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [Python os.open documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html#os.open)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a37028dc-7d77-3b4c-94be-6d5ee7cb5753",
              "name": "GET Route Performs State-Changing Action",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is a state-changing action exposed through a GET request, which creates a cross-site request forgery risk. In this Flask view, visiting the route can reset the user's MFA secret by calling libmfa.mfa_reset_secret, even though GET should be safe and not modify server-side state.\n\nBecause browsers automatically issue GET requests for links, images, and embedded content, an attacker can cause a logged-in user to trigger this endpoint without intending to. For this route, the fix is to separate display from mutation: keep GET for rendering the page, and move MFA secret reset or enable actions to a POST-only endpoint protected with a CSRF token.\n\nIn Python Flask applications, CSRF protection is commonly enforced with Flask-WTF. The handler should render the MFA setup page on GET, then accept a POST from a form that includes a CSRF token before resetting the secret and generating the provisioning QR code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not perform account changes, token rotation, secret generation, deletion, or any other server-side mutation in a GET handler. Reserve GET for safe reads and require POST, PUT, PATCH, or DELETE for actions that change state.\n\nEnable CSRF protection for all state-changing routes and validate a per-request token bound to the user session. In Flask, initialize CSRF protection centrally and ensure forms that trigger MFA enrollment, reset, disablement, or recovery submit via POST with a validated token. As an additional defense, avoid making sensitive actions happen automatically on page load and consider re-authentication for MFA reset flows.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom io import BytesIO\nimport base64\n\nimport pyotp\nimport qrcode\nfrom flask import Blueprint, g, redirect, render_template, request\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import SubmitField\n\nmod_mfa = Blueprint('mod_mfa', __name__)\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\n\n\nclass ResetMFAForm(FlaskForm):\n    submit = SubmitField('Generate new MFA secret')\n\n\n@mod_mfa.route('/', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_mfa_view():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    username = g.session['username']\n    form = ResetMFAForm()\n\n    if libmfa.mfa_is_enabled(username):\n        return render_template('mfa.disable.html', form=form)\n\n    if request.method == 'POST' and form.validate_on_submit():\n        libmfa.mfa_reset_secret(username)\n        secret = libmfa.mfa_get_secret(username)\n        secret_url = pyotp.totp.TOTP(secret).provisioning_uri(username, issuer_name='Vulpy')\n        img = qrcode.make(secret_url)\n\n        buffered = BytesIO()\n        img.save(buffered, format='PNG')\n        img_str = base64.b64encode(buffered.getvalue()).decode()\n\n        return render_template('mfa.enable.html', form=form, secret_url=secret_url, img_str=img_str)\n\n    return render_template('mfa.enable.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
