                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a3e25d77-cf1f-3d7f-823d-0f5f469e5830",
              "name": "Debug Mode Enabled In Production Environment",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an active debug mode in production vulnerability. In Python Flask applications, starting the development server with debug enabled can expose stack traces, configuration details, environment data, and other sensitive internals to users when errors occur.\n\nIn the shown sink, the application is launched with app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', ssl_context=(...)). Even when TLS is configured, debug mode still enables development-only behavior that is unsafe outside local development. The fix is to disable debug explicitly in code and drive environment-specific behavior through Flask configuration or environment variables, while using a production WSGI server for deployment.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not hardcode debug=True in Flask startup code. Default DEBUG to false and only enable it in a controlled local development environment through configuration or environment variables. For deployed environments, serve the application with a production-grade WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI instead of relying on Flask's built-in development server. Keep detailed error information in server-side logs and return generic error responses to clients.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config.from_mapping(\n    DEBUG=os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\"\n)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    app.run(\n        debug=app.config[\"DEBUG\"],\n        host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n        ssl_context=(\"/tmp/acme.cert\", \"/tmp/acme.key\")\n    )\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask\ngunicorn\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Flask Documentation: Debug Mode](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#debug-mode)\n- [OWASP: Information Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Information_exposure_through_query_strings_in_url)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a7419fd1-d235-3486-8933-e47678171974",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Writing directly to a predictable path under /tmp in Python can let another local user interfere with the file before or during use.\n\nIn this sink, opening /tmp/acme.csr with open(..., \"wb\") creates or truncates a file at a globally shared location using a fixed name. On multi-user systems this can enable symlink attacks, clobber an existing file, expose sensitive request data, or cause the program to read or write the wrong file. The risk is higher for certificate signing requests because they may contain sensitive key-related metadata.\n\nUse Python's tempfile module to create the file securely with a unique name and restrictive permissions, or avoid the filesystem entirely if the CSR only needs to be passed to another function. If a persistent file is required, create a private directory first and place the file there instead of writing to a predictable name in /tmp.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not construct temporary file paths manually in shared directories such as /tmp. Use tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile, tempfile.mkstemp, or tempfile.TemporaryDirectory so the operating system creates a unique file atomically with safe permissions. When possible, keep sensitive data in memory instead of writing it to disk. If the file must persist after creation, store it in a directory owned by the current process with restrictive permissions and remove it as soon as it is no longer needed. Also avoid following user-controlled paths or symlinks for temporary artifacts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport tempfile\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\ncsr_bytes = build_csr_bytes()\n\nwith tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(mode=\"wb\", suffix=\".csr\", prefix=\"acme-\", delete=False) as out:\n    out.write(csr_bytes)\n    csr_path = Path(out.name)\n\nprocess_csr_file(csr_path)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ntempfile\npathlib\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a89e76a8-eb08-33ea-8322-533d074a74af",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery protection is missing on a state-changing Flask endpoint. This route accepts POSTed credential and MFA data, clears and creates session state, and performs authentication changes without any visible CSRF token validation.\n\nIn Flask, a browser will automatically attach the victim's cookies to cross-site form submissions unless the application explicitly defends against them. That means another site can cause a victim's browser to submit a POST request to this login endpoint, potentially forcing unwanted authentication flow changes or session confusion.\n\nProtect this route at the framework layer by enabling CSRF validation for POST requests and embedding a server-generated token in the rendered form. For login and similar sensitive endpoints, also harden session cookies with SameSite and Secure settings. If you need an additional defense, validate the Origin header on unsafe methods before processing the request.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally for the Flask application so every unsafe method is validated by default instead of relying on per-route checks. Use Flask-WTF or equivalent server-side token validation, ensure templates include the hidden token field, and reject requests with missing or invalid tokens.\n\nFor authentication endpoints, also set SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE, SESSION_COOKIE_HTTPONLY, and SESSION_COOKIE_SAMESITE to reduce cross-site abuse. If the endpoint is intended only for same-site browser use, enforce an Origin check for POST requests as a secondary defense, but do not use Origin or Referer validation as a replacement for CSRF tokens.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Blueprint, flash, make_response, redirect, render_template, request, session, abort, current_app\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import PasswordField, StringField, SubmitField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\n\nmod_user = Blueprint(\"mod_user\", __name__)\n\n\nclass LoginForm(FlaskForm):\n    username = StringField(\"Username\", validators=[DataRequired()])\n    password = PasswordField(\"Password\", validators=[DataRequired()])\n    otp = StringField(\"OTP\")\n    submit = SubmitField(\"Sign in\")\n\n\ndef _validate_same_origin():\n    origin = request.headers.get(\"Origin\")\n    if origin and origin != request.host_url.rstrip(\"/\"):\n        abort(403)\n\n\n@mod_user.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_login():\n    form = LoginForm()\n\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        _validate_same_origin()\n        if not form.validate_on_submit():\n            flash(\"Invalid or missing form token\")\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html', form=form), 400\n\n        session.pop('username', None)\n\n        username = form.username.data\n        password = form.password.data\n        otp = form.otp.data\n\n        username = libuser.login(username, password)\n\n        if not username:\n            flash(\"Invalid user or password\")\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html', form=form)\n\n        if libmfa.mfa_is_enabled(username):\n            if not libmfa.mfa_validate(username, otp):\n                flash(\"Invalid OTP\")\n                return render_template('user.login.mfa.html', form=form)\n\n        response = make_response(redirect('/'))\n        response = libsession.create(response=response, username=username)\n        return response\n\n    return render_template('user.login.mfa.html', form=form)\n\n\n# Application setup example:\n# app.config['SECRET_KEY'] = 'replace-with-a-long-random-secret'\n# app.config['WTF_CSRF_TIME_LIMIT'] = 3600\n# app.config['SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE'] = True\n# app.config['SESSION_COOKIE_HTTPONLY'] = True\n# app.config['SESSION_COOKIE_SAMESITE'] = 'Lax'\n# csrf.init_app(app)\n\n# In user.login.mfa.html, render the hidden CSRF field inside the form:\n# <form method=\"post\">\n#   {{ form.hidden_tag() }}\n#   {{ form.username() }}\n#   {{ form.password() }}\n#   {{ form.otp() }}\n#   {{ form.submit() }}\n# </form>\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Security Considerations](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/web-security/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a8ecdbb7-6f44-3d7f-9dca-0e0c89821dcf",
              "name": "Insecure Use Of App Run In Flask",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nImproper top-level startup of a development web server. In Python, calling Flask's app.run(...) at import time causes the server to start whenever the module is imported, which can lead to unintended execution during testing, tooling, multiprocessing, or production deployment. Flask also expects application startup to be guarded so imports remain side-effect free.\n\nIn this case, the application starts the built-in Flask development server with debug mode enabled and a fixed local bind address. Debug mode should not be enabled outside local development because it increases exposure of sensitive internals and changes runtime behavior. Move the startup behind a __main__ guard and keep debug disabled by default so the module can be safely imported by a real WSGI server or other application code.\n\nIf HTTPS is needed for local development, keeping ssl_context is acceptable, but the certificate and key paths should be sourced from controlled configuration rather than hard-coded in executable startup code. For production, run the Flask app under a supported WSGI server and terminate TLS with the deployment stack or server configuration instead of relying on app.run(...).\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nKeep Flask application modules import-safe by avoiding server startup at the top level. Put app.run(...) inside a main function and call it only under if __name__ == \"__main__\" so imports do not trigger side effects. Disable debug by default and enable it only through controlled development configuration.\n\nDo not use the built-in development server as the production entry point. Expose the Flask app object for a WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI, and handle TLS with the deployment environment. When local TLS is required, load certificate paths from environment variables or other trusted configuration instead of embedding file paths directly in code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Flask\nimport os\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\n\ndef main() -> None:\n    debug = os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\"\n    cert_path = os.getenv(\"FLASK_CERT_PATH\")\n    key_path = os.getenv(\"FLASK_KEY_PATH\")\n    ssl_context = (cert_path, key_path) if cert_path and key_path else None\n\n    app.run(\n        debug=debug,\n        host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n        ssl_context=ssl_context,\n    )\n\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nflask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Development Server](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/server/)\n- [Python __main__ — Top-level code environment](https://docs.python.org/3/library/__main__.html)\n- [Deploying to Production](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/deploying/)\n- [Werkzeug Serving](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/serving/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-668",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/668.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-668"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "aaee5403-4174-3c3b-9e12-6a1eaf31dac3",
              "name": "Login Route Lacks Rate Limiting And Throttling",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an insufficient protection against brute-force authentication attempts issue. The login route accepts repeated username, password, and OTP submissions, but there is no visible rate limiting, failed-attempt counter, temporary lockout, or progressive delay to slow automated guessing.\n\nIn this Flask handler, an attacker can repeatedly post credentials to /login and receive immediate feedback for invalid password and invalid OTP cases. That makes the endpoint suitable for password spraying, credential stuffing, and MFA code guessing. The fix is to throttle the route and track failures per account and client source, then enforce a short lockout or backoff before continuing authentication.\n\nFor this sink, apply request throttling directly on the login endpoint and add failure bookkeeping around both the password check and the OTP check. Reset the failure counter only after the full authentication flow succeeds, and return the same generic error response for all authentication failures to reduce account enumeration and feedback to attackers.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nProtect authentication endpoints with layered controls. Apply per-IP and per-account rate limits, maintain failed-attempt counters, and enforce temporary lockouts or exponential backoff after repeated failures. If the application is deployed on multiple workers or servers, store counters in a shared backend such as Redis instead of process memory so throttling remains consistent.\n\nUse the same generic error message and similar response behavior for invalid username, password, and OTP failures. Reset counters only after the entire login and MFA sequence succeeds. Log lockouts and repeated failures for monitoring, and consider adding CAPTCHA or secondary challenges only after suspicious activity thresholds are reached, not as the sole defense.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import current_app, flash, make_response, redirect, render_template, request, session\nfrom flask_limiter import Limiter\nfrom flask_limiter.util import get_remote_address\nfrom time import time\n\nlimiter = Limiter(key_func=get_remote_address, default_limits=[])\n\n_failed_logins = {}\n_LOCKOUT_SECONDS = 900\n_MAX_ATTEMPTS = 5\n\n\ndef _client_key(username):\n    return f\"{get_remote_address()}:{(username or '').strip().lower()}\"\n\n\ndef _is_locked(key):\n    entry = _failed_logins.get(key)\n    if not entry:\n        return False\n    if entry[\"count\"] < _MAX_ATTEMPTS:\n        return False\n    if time() >= entry[\"locked_until\"]:\n        _failed_logins.pop(key, None)\n        return False\n    return True\n\n\ndef _record_failure(key):\n    now = time()\n    entry = _failed_logins.get(key, {\"count\": 0, \"locked_until\": 0})\n    entry[\"count\"] += 1\n    if entry[\"count\"] >= _MAX_ATTEMPTS:\n        entry[\"locked_until\"] = now + _LOCKOUT_SECONDS\n    _failed_logins[key] = entry\n\n\ndef _reset_failures(key):\n    _failed_logins.pop(key, None)\n\n\n@mod_user.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\n@limiter.limit(\"10 per minute\")\ndef do_login():\n    session.pop('username', None)\n\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        username = request.form.get('username', '')\n        password = request.form.get('password', '')\n        otp = request.form.get('otp', '')\n\n        key = _client_key(username)\n        if _is_locked(key):\n            flash(\"Invalid authentication credentials\")\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 429\n\n        authenticated_username = libuser.login(username, password)\n        if not authenticated_username:\n            _record_failure(key)\n            flash(\"Invalid authentication credentials\")\n            return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 401\n\n        if libmfa.mfa_is_enabled(authenticated_username):\n            if not libmfa.mfa_validate(authenticated_username, otp):\n                _record_failure(key)\n                flash(\"Invalid authentication credentials\")\n                return render_template('user.login.mfa.html'), 401\n\n        _reset_failures(key)\n        response = make_response(redirect('/'))\n        response = libsession.create(response=response, username=authenticated_username)\n        return response\n\n    return render_template('user.login.mfa.html')\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-Limiter\nredis\nfrom flask_limiter import Limiter\nfrom flask_limiter.util import get_remote_address\nfrom time import time\nfrom flask import flash, make_response, redirect, render_template, request, session\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Blocking Brute Force Attacks](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/Blocking_Brute_Force_Attacks)\n- [OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authentication_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-307: Improper Restriction of Excessive Authentication Attempts](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/307.html)\n- [Flask-Limiter Documentation](https://flask-limiter.readthedocs.io/en/stable/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-307",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/307.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-307"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b0656179-b579-3232-91b0-8941f05cd897",
              "name": "Weak Or Broken Hash Function Used",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an insecure hash algorithm issue: the code computes a digest through hashlib.new(ALGORITHM, ...) where the selected algorithm may be MD5 or SHA-1. In Python, that pattern is especially risky when the algorithm name is configurable, because a weak choice can be introduced at runtime and silently used for security-sensitive processing.\n\nMD5 and SHA-1 are no longer appropriate for passwords, signatures, or integrity checks that need collision resistance or resistance to offline attacks. If lastkey is being transformed for authentication or credential storage, a fast general-purpose hash is the wrong primitive entirely. If it is being hashed for general integrity or token derivation, the code should restrict the algorithm to a strong modern hash such as SHA-256 or SHA-512.\n\nFor the sink shown here, replace dynamic selection with an explicit strong algorithm when a plain digest is actually intended. If the value represents a password or other secret that must resist brute-force guessing, use a password-based key derivation function such as hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac with a unique random salt and a high iteration count instead of hexdigest() on the raw input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not allow weak hash names such as md5 or sha1 to flow into hashlib.new for security-sensitive operations. Prefer explicit algorithm selection in code so the primitive cannot be downgraded through configuration or input. For passwords or similar secrets, use a password KDF with a per-value random salt and sufficient work factor; store the salt alongside the derived value and compare derived values using constant-time comparison when verifying. If the use case is not password storage but a normal digest, switch to hashlib.sha256 or stronger and document that only modern algorithms are permitted.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport hashlib\nimport os\n\nlastkey_bytes = lastkey.encode(\"utf-8\")\n\nsalt = os.urandom(16)\nderived_key = hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac(\"sha256\", lastkey_bytes, salt, 600000)\nlastkey = derived_key.hex()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nhashlib\nos\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)\n- [Python hashlib documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html)\n- [Python hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html#hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b3f84613-342e-3f81-965b-e92c9364ce4f",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Writing directly to a predictable path such as /tmp/ca.cert in Python can expose the file to race conditions, symlink attacks, overwrites by other users, or unintended disclosure because shared temporary directories are typically writable by multiple accounts.\n\nIn this sink, the code opens a fixed filename under /tmp and writes certificate data to it. An attacker on the same system can pre-create the path, replace it with a symbolic link, or read the file if permissions are too broad. For security-sensitive content such as certificate material, create the file with the tempfile module so the name is unique and the file is created securely, and restrict permissions to the current process or user.\n\nIf the file must persist, use tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile or tempfile.mkstemp instead of open() on a hard-coded path, set restrictive permissions, and remove the file when it is no longer needed. If persistence is not required, use a temporary file object managed by the standard library and avoid exposing a filesystem path at all.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hard-coded filenames in shared temporary directories. Use Python's tempfile APIs to create temporary files atomically with unpredictable names. Keep permissions as restrictive as possible, especially for certificate, key, token, or configuration data. Prefer file descriptors returned by secure creation APIs over separate existence checks and open calls, because separate steps introduce race conditions. Delete temporary files promptly after use, or use higher-level temporary file objects when a persistent path is unnecessary.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, temp_path = tempfile.mkstemp(suffix=\".cert\")\ntry:\n    os.fchmod(fd, 0o600)\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as out:\n        out.write(cert_data)\n\n    # use temp_path as needed\nfinally:\n    if os.path.exists(temp_path):\n        os.remove(temp_path)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-379: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html)\n- [Python tempfile module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-379",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/379.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-379"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b512c722-1030-3cde-aa69-de3b13b00c63",
              "name": "Insecure HTTP Transport Used",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure transport over HTTP. This Python code sends a POST request to an API endpoint using plain HTTP, which exposes the request body and headers to interception or modification by anyone with network access between the client and server.\n\nIn this sink, both the message content and the API key are transmitted without transport encryption. Replace the endpoint with an HTTPS URL and keep TLS certificate verification enabled so the client can authenticate the server and protect the confidentiality and integrity of the request.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse HTTPS for all outbound requests that carry application data, credentials, session tokens, or API keys. Do not send secrets over http:// URLs. In Python, let requests perform TLS certificate verification by default and do not disable it with verify=False. If the service is internal or uses a private CA, configure the server with a valid certificate and point the client at the trusted CA bundle rather than falling back to plaintext transport. Also set a reasonable timeout and handle HTTP errors explicitly.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport requests\n\nurl = \"https://127.0.1.1:5000/api/post\"\nr = requests.post(\n    url,\n    json={\"text\": message},\n    headers={\"X-APIKEY\": api_key},\n    timeout=10,\n)\nr.raise_for_status()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nrequests\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insecure Transport](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Transport)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)\n- [Requests: SSL Cert Verification](https://requests.readthedocs.io/en/latest/user/advanced/#ssl-cert-verification)\n- [Python ssl module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/ssl.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
