            {
              "id": "b98ba7b4-e8b3-3ced-b6bc-fd96a21470d2",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. This code starts a Python web application with TLS material loaded from files under /tmp, which is a shared temporary directory on Unix-like systems. Certificate and private key files stored there can be replaced, read, or linked by other local users or processes if file creation and permissions are not tightly controlled.\n\nIn this sink, ssl_context points to /tmp/acme.cert and /tmp/acme.key while the application is also running in debug mode. A private key should be kept in a dedicated protected location with restrictive permissions, not in a world-writable temporary path. Move the certificate and key to an application-controlled directory, ensure the key file is readable only by the service account, and disable debug mode outside local development.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not store certificate or private key files in shared temporary directories such as /tmp. Keep TLS assets in a dedicated directory owned by the application or service account, set the private key permissions to owner-read only, and verify the path is not a symlink before loading it. In Python, prefer pathlib and os.stat or os.open-based checks to enforce expected ownership and mode before use.\n\nDo not use the built-in debug server for deployed environments. Run the application behind a production WSGI server and terminate TLS with properly managed certificates, or load certificates from a protected secrets or configuration location. If temporary files are genuinely required elsewhere in the application, create them with Python's tempfile APIs so they are created securely with restrictive permissions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nBASE_DIR = Path(\"/etc/myapp/tls\")\nCERT_FILE = BASE_DIR / \"acme.cert\"\nKEY_FILE = BASE_DIR / \"acme.key\"\n\nkey_stat = os.stat(KEY_FILE)\nif key_stat.st_mode & 0o077:\n    raise PermissionError(\"TLS private key permissions must be 600 or stricter\")\n\napp.run(\n    debug=False,\n    host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n    ssl_context=(str(CERT_FILE), str(KEY_FILE)),\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nflask\nwerkzeug\npython >=3.8\nopenssl (system package for certificate management)\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Flask Development Server Documentation](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/server/)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c1440400-b81d-3954-9865-7d78e40816aa",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. Opening a fixed path under /tmp in Python is unsafe because that directory is shared and world-writable on many systems. An attacker can pre-create, replace, or symlink /tmp/acme.pub so the code reads unexpected content or accesses a different file than intended.\n\nIn this sink, the code reads a public key from a predictable temporary filename. If another local user or process can influence that path, key material loading can be redirected and trust decisions can be subverted. Mitigate this by avoiding hard-coded names in shared temporary directories, creating the file with secure temporary-file APIs, restricting permissions, and reopening only a file you created yourself.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use predictable filenames in shared temporary locations such as /tmp. Use Python's tempfile module to create a unique file or directory securely, keep permissions as restrictive as possible, and avoid following attacker-controlled paths. If the file is meant to persist, place it in an application-owned directory with controlled ownership and mode instead of a global temp directory. When reading sensitive or security-relevant content such as keys, ensure the file was created by the current process and validate its location and permissions before use.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport tempfile\n\nwith tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(mode=\"wb\", delete=False) as tmp:\n    tmp_path = Path(tmp.name)\n\ntry:\n    tmp_path.chmod(0o600)\n    # Write the expected key data to tmp_path before reading it if needed.\n    with tmp_path.open(\"rb\") as key_file:\n        key_data = key_file.read()\nfinally:\n    tmp_path.unlink(missing_ok=True)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ntempfile\npathlib\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [Python pathlib module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/pathlib.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c16f1270-f01e-389a-ac1c-8fbe6bbaf464",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery in a state-changing Flask POST route. This handler creates a post using the authenticated session and trusts form data from any POST request, but it does not show a CSRF token check or a same-origin validation step before calling the write operation.\n\nIn Flask applications, session cookies are sent automatically by the browser. Without CSRF protection, an attacker can cause a logged-in user to submit a forged POST request from another site, resulting in unintended content creation under that user's account. For this route, the fix is to enforce CSRF validation at the framework level and require a token on the form that submits text.\n\nA robust remediation is to enable Flask-WTF CSRFProtect for the application and validate a hidden csrf_token field on the form rendered to the user. As defense in depth, keep the route restricted to POST for state changes and consider rejecting cross-origin requests by checking Origin or Referer when appropriate.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally for the Flask application rather than trying to protect individual handlers manually. For HTML form workflows, use Flask-WTF CSRFProtect and FlaskForm so POST requests are rejected unless they include a valid per-session token. Ensure the form template renders the hidden token field with form.hidden_tag() or the csrf_token field explicitly.\n\nKeep state-changing actions limited to POST, PUT, PATCH, or DELETE, and do not rely on checking request.method alone as a CSRF defense. If some endpoints are not form-based, add a same-origin check using the Origin header, or Referer as a fallback, and set session cookies with Secure and SameSite=Lax or Strict where compatible. Avoid disabling CSRF on authenticated routes that modify server state.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import Flask, Blueprint, g, redirect, render_template, request\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import TextAreaField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired, Length\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config['SECRET_KEY'] = 'replace-with-a-strong-random-secret'\ncsrf = CSRFProtect(app)\n\nmod_posts = Blueprint('posts', __name__)\n\n\nclass PostForm(FlaskForm):\n    text = TextAreaField(validators=[DataRequired(), Length(max=5000)])\n\n\n@mod_posts.route('/', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_create():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/user/login')\n\n    form = PostForm()\n    if form.validate_on_submit():\n        username = g.session['username']\n        libposts.post(username, form.text.data)\n        return redirect('/')\n\n    return render_template('create_post.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://owasp.org/www-project-cheat-sheets/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n- [Flask Security Considerations](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/web-security/)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c3e435a2-8660-34ac-82d2-e72c5d898b67",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. Opening a fixed path under /tmp in Python is unsafe because that directory is shared and world-writable on many systems. An attacker can pre-create, replace, or symlink /tmp/acme.pub so the code reads unexpected content or accesses a different file than intended.\n\nIn this sink, the code reads a public key from a predictable temporary filename. If another local user or process can influence that path, key material loading can be redirected and trust decisions can be subverted. Mitigate this by avoiding hard-coded names in shared temporary directories, creating the file with secure temporary-file APIs, restricting permissions, and reopening only a file you created yourself.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use predictable filenames in shared temporary locations such as /tmp. Use Python's tempfile module to create a unique file or directory securely, keep permissions as restrictive as possible, and avoid following attacker-controlled paths. If the file is meant to persist, place it in an application-owned directory with controlled ownership and mode instead of a global temp directory. When reading sensitive or security-relevant content such as keys, ensure the file was created by the current process and validate its location and permissions before use.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport tempfile\n\nwith tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(mode=\"wb\", delete=False) as tmp:\n    tmp_path = Path(tmp.name)\n\ntry:\n    tmp_path.chmod(0o600)\n    # Write the expected key data to tmp_path before reading it if needed.\n    with tmp_path.open(\"rb\") as key_file:\n        key_data = key_file.read()\nfinally:\n    tmp_path.unlink(missing_ok=True)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ntempfile\npathlib\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [Python pathlib module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/pathlib.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377"
                ]
              }
