            {
              "id": "c7080e25-fb7b-3b01-aec0-fbdf1fc75995",
              "name": "Missing Function Level Access Control",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is a function-level access control weakness. The view-like function reads a session cookie directly and returns session data without any authentication or authorization check, which can allow unauthenticated callers to reach code paths that should be restricted.\n\nIn Python web applications, access control should be enforced at the request handler boundary with framework-supported authentication and authorization mechanisms, not by manually decoding untrusted cookies. The current code trusts client-controlled cookie content, silently ignores parsing errors, and does not verify whether the caller is logged in or permitted to access the resource. Protect the endpoint with login and permission checks, and use the framework's signed server-side session handling instead of custom cookie deserialization.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nRequire authentication on the handler and enforce authorization for the specific action or resource before returning data. Use your Python web framework's built-in session and identity features so cookies are signed or stored server-side and cannot be safely forged by clients. Do not deserialize raw cookie values into trusted session state. Also avoid broad exception handling that suppresses security-relevant failures; reject invalid session material and return an appropriate unauthorized or forbidden response. If this code is part of Django, use login_required, permission_required, request.user, and request.session. If it is part of Flask, use Flask-Login or equivalent decorators and store authorization decisions on the server side.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom django.contrib.auth.decorators import login_required, permission_required\nfrom django.http import JsonResponse\n\n@login_required\n@permission_required('app.view_session', raise_exception=True)\ndef load(request):\n    session_data = {\n        'user_id': request.user.id,\n        'username': request.user.get_username(),\n        'is_authenticated': request.user.is_authenticated,\n    }\n    return JsonResponse(session_data)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nDjango\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-community/Broken_Access_Control)\n- [OWASP Authorization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authorization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [Django authentication and authorization](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/stable/topics/auth/default/)\n- [Flask view decorators](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/patterns/viewdecorators/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c838b9ae-7158-3a0f-85a1-ae1641f89dad",
              "name": "Debug Mode Enabled In Production Environment",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nActive debug mode in production can expose sensitive information and unsafe developer features. In a Flask application, running the server with debug=True enables the interactive debugger, detailed stack traces, automatic code reloading, and verbose error output that should not be available to end users or untrusted networks.\n\nFor the shown sink, app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', port=5001, extra_files='csp.txt'), the fix is to disable debug mode in code and control it through application configuration or environment-specific settings. This ensures the application starts safely by default while still allowing debugging during local development when explicitly enabled outside production.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not hardcode debug=True in deployed Flask applications. Keep debug disabled by default and enable it only in local development through environment variables or a dedicated development configuration. Avoid exposing the built-in development server to untrusted users, and use a production-grade WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI for deployed environments. Restrict detailed error pages and stack traces so failures are logged internally instead of being returned to clients.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    debug_enabled = os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\"\n    app.run(\n        debug=debug_enabled,\n        host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n        port=5001,\n        extra_files=[\"csp.txt\"]\n    )\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debug Mode](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Flask Documentation: Configuration Handling](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#debug-mode)\n- [OWASP: Information Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Information_exposure_through_query_strings_in_url)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c8b9cbff-c720-3f8c-9186-cd803860428b",
              "name": "Missing CSRF Protection In State-Changing Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-site request forgery in a state-changing Flask POST route. This password-change handler accepts form data and updates account state based only on the user session, so a malicious site can cause a logged-in browser to submit a forged POST request to this endpoint.\n\nIn Flask applications, session cookies are automatically sent by the browser, which means checking that the user is authenticated is not sufficient protection for sensitive actions like changing a password. The route should require a server-generated CSRF token and reject requests with a missing or invalid token. For additional defense, validate the request Origin or Referer against your own host before processing the form.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nEnable CSRF protection globally in the Flask application and use a form class that embeds and validates a CSRF token for every state-changing POST, PUT, PATCH, or DELETE endpoint. In the template for this route, render the hidden CSRF field so each submitted form carries the token generated for the user session.\n\nFor sensitive actions such as password changes, add an Origin or Referer allow check as a second layer of defense and reject requests that do not come from your own site. Keep session cookies protected with Secure and SameSite settings, but do not rely on cookie attributes alone in place of token validation. Also preserve user-facing validation for current password and password policy after CSRF checks succeed.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom flask import abort, flash, redirect, render_template, request, url_for\nfrom flask_wtf import FlaskForm, CSRFProtect\nfrom wtforms import PasswordField\nfrom wtforms.validators import DataRequired, EqualTo\nfrom urllib.parse import urlparse\n\ncsrf = CSRFProtect()\n\n\ndef init_app(app):\n    app.config.setdefault('SECRET_KEY', 'change-this-secret-key')\n    app.config.setdefault('WTF_CSRF_TIME_LIMIT', 3600)\n    csrf.init_app(app)\n\n\nclass ChangePasswordForm(FlaskForm):\n    current_password = PasswordField('Current password', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    new_password = PasswordField('New password', validators=[DataRequired()])\n    new_password_again = PasswordField(\n        'Repeat new password',\n        validators=[DataRequired(), EqualTo('new_password', message='The passwords do not match')]\n    )\n\n\n@mod_user.route('/chpasswd', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef do_chpasswd_post():\n    if 'username' not in g.session:\n        return redirect('/')\n\n    form = ChangePasswordForm()\n\n    if request.method == 'POST':\n        origin = request.headers.get('Origin')\n        referer = request.headers.get('Referer')\n        expected_origin = request.host_url.rstrip('/')\n\n        if origin:\n            if origin.rstrip('/') != expected_origin:\n                abort(403)\n        elif referer:\n            if urlparse(referer).netloc != urlparse(expected_origin).netloc:\n                abort(403)\n        else:\n            abort(403)\n\n        if form.validate_on_submit():\n            if not libuser.login(g.session['username'], form.current_password.data):\n                flash('Invalid current password')\n                return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form)\n\n            if not libuser.is_password_allowed(form.new_password.data):\n                flash('The password does not comply with requirements, please choose another one.')\n                return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form)\n\n            libuser.password_set(g.session['username'], form.new_password.data)\n            flash('Password changed')\n            return redirect(url_for('mod_user.do_chpasswd_post'))\n\n    return render_template('user.chpasswd.html', form=form)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask-WTF\nWTForms\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/csrf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Request Forgery Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)\n- [Flask-WTF CSRF Protection](https://flask-wtf.readthedocs.io/en/1.2.x/csrf/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d53787a8-fd0f-373b-9516-bb622994737f",
              "name": "Missing Function Level Access Control",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is a missing authentication and authorization control issue. In Python web applications, sensitive endpoints must enforce identity checks and permission checks before executing protected functionality.\n\nThe shown helper trusts a custom X-APIKEY header and performs authentication by matching attacker-controlled input against filenames under /tmp using a glob pattern. That design is unsafe because /tmp is a shared, writable location on many systems, the key is not validated against a trusted credential store, and the first matching file determines the identity. If a view relies on this function without a proper authentication or authorization decorator, an attacker can reach protected behavior by supplying crafted headers or by influencing files on disk.\n\nThe fix is to move authentication to a trusted framework mechanism, validate API keys against a server-controlled store, and require authorization checks at the view or route boundary. In Python, this is typically done with a decorator that rejects unauthenticated requests and verifies the authenticated principal has permission to access the requested function or resource.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nProtect every sensitive route with server-side authentication and authorization checks, not just helper functions that a caller may forget to invoke. Do not derive identity from filenames, glob patterns, temporary directories, or other untrusted filesystem state. Store API keys in a trusted backend or configuration secret store, compare them with constant-time checks, and map them to explicit principals and roles.\n\nPrefer the authentication and permission features provided by the Python web framework in use, such as decorators, middleware, or dependency injection, so access control is enforced consistently. Return 401 for missing or invalid credentials and 403 for authenticated users lacking permission. Keep secrets out of source code, rotate keys regularly, and log denied access attempts without exposing credential values.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom functools import wraps\nimport hmac\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask, abort, g, request\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\nAPI_KEYS = {\n    os.environ.get(\"API_KEY_ADMIN\", \"\"): {\"username\": \"admin\", \"roles\": {\"admin\"}},\n    os.environ.get(\"API_KEY_USER\", \"\"): {\"username\": \"user\", \"roles\": {\"user\"}},\n}\n\n\ndef authenticate(request):\n    key = request.headers.get(\"X-APIKEY\")\n    if not key:\n        return None\n\n    for stored_key, principal in API_KEYS.items():\n        if stored_key and hmac.compare_digest(key, stored_key):\n            return principal\n\n    return None\n\n\ndef require_auth(required_role=None):\n    def decorator(view_func):\n        @wraps(view_func)\n        def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n            principal = authenticate(request)\n            if principal is None:\n                abort(401)\n\n            if required_role and required_role not in principal[\"roles\"]:\n                abort(403)\n\n            g.principal = principal\n            return view_func(*args, **kwargs)\n        return wrapper\n    return decorator\n\n\n@app.route(\"/admin\")\n@require_auth(\"admin\")\ndef admin_panel():\n    return {\"user\": g.principal[\"username\"], \"status\": \"ok\"}\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nflask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-community/Broken_Access_Control)\n- [OWASP Authorization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authorization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-306: Missing Authentication for Critical Function](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html)\n- [CWE-862: Missing Authorization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-306",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/306.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-862",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-306",
                  "CWE-862"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d6aa8297-1187-36a5-8883-8a671755c279",
              "name": "Debug Mode Enabled In Production Environment",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an active debug mode vulnerability. In a Python Flask application, running the development server with debug enabled exposes detailed error pages, stack traces, environment information, and interactive debugging features that are unsafe in production.\n\nIn the shown sink, app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', port=5000, extra_files='csp.txt') explicitly enables Flask debug mode at runtime. Even if the service is bound to a local interface, this setting increases the risk of sensitive information disclosure and unsafe debugging behavior if the application is deployed outside a controlled development environment. The fix is to remove the hard-coded debug flag, default it to disabled, and control it through environment-specific configuration instead.\n\nFor Flask, keep debug off in production and use application configuration or environment variables to enable it only for local development. This makes the runtime behavior explicit, reduces accidental exposure during deployment, and keeps development conveniences separate from production execution.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not hard-code debug=True in Flask startup code. Keep debug disabled by default and enable it only in local development through configuration or environment variables such as FLASK_DEBUG. Use a production-grade WSGI server for deployed environments, and ensure verbose error pages and interactive debuggers are never exposed to users. Review deployment settings so that development-only options, including automatic reload behavior and extra file watching, are not carried into production.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    debug_enabled = os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\"\n    app.run(\n        debug=debug_enabled,\n        host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n        port=5000,\n        extra_files=[\"csp.txt\"]\n    )\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nflask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Flask Documentation: Debug Mode](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#debug-mode)\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d73a5990-54d9-3a0d-9588-ee32114a47a1",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Reading a certificate from a fixed path under /tmp is unsafe in Python because /tmp is typically world-writable and shared by multiple users and processes. An attacker can pre-create, replace, or symlink /tmp/ca.cert so the application reads untrusted content instead of the expected certificate.\n\nFor the sink shown, the risk is especially important because the file appears to be used as a CA certificate. If a malicious file is substituted, certificate validation can be subverted and trusted connections may be redirected or intercepted. Mitigate this by avoiding predictable names in shared temporary directories, creating temporary files with secure APIs when temporary storage is required, and preferring a trusted application-controlled path with restrictive permissions for security-sensitive certificate material.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use hard-coded, predictable filenames in shared temporary directories such as /tmp for sensitive files. Store certificates and other trust anchors in an application-owned directory with permissions restricted to the service account, and validate ownership and mode before use when appropriate. If temporary storage is unavoidable, create files with Python's tempfile module so names are unpredictable and files are opened securely. Also prefer passing certificate data directly to the consuming API instead of reopening it from a temporary path whenever the library supports in-memory loading.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport ssl\nimport tempfile\n\ntrusted_ca_path = Path(\"/etc/myapp/ca.cert\")\nwith trusted_ca_path.open(\"rb\") as ca_cert_file:\n    ca_bytes = ca_cert_file.read()\n\ncontext = ssl.create_default_context()\ncontext.load_verify_locations(cadata=ca_bytes.decode(\"ascii\"))\n\nwith tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(mode=\"wb\", delete=True) as temp_file:\n    temp_file.write(ca_bytes)\n    temp_file.flush()\n    with open(temp_file.name, \"rb\") as ca_cert_file:\n        data = ca_cert_file.read()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\npathlib\nssl\ntempfile\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d8af9b34-61fb-3d1d-b42e-f6d41de03587",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. Writing directly to a predictable path under /tmp in Python can let another local user or process interfere with the file through pre-creation, symlink redirection, or permission abuse.\n\nIn the shown sink, opening /tmp/acme.cert with open(..., 'wb') trusts a shared world-writable directory and a fixed filename. An attacker on the same host can race to replace that path, point it at another file, or read sensitive certificate material if permissions are too broad. This is especially risky for certificate, key, token, or other security-relevant output.\n\nUse Python's tempfile APIs to create a unique file securely, or create the file with exclusive creation semantics and restrictive permissions. If the file must have a stable final name, write it to a securely created temporary file in a trusted directory and then atomically replace the destination after setting ownership and mode appropriately.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid fixed filenames in shared temporary directories. Create temporary files with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile or tempfile.mkstemp so the name is unique and the file is created securely by the operating system. Restrict permissions to the minimum required, typically 0o600 for certificate-like material.\n\nIf a predictable final pathname is required, create the content in a securely created temporary file first, then move it into place with os.replace. Prefer an application-controlled directory over /tmp when possible, verify ownership and permissions of that directory, and never follow user-influenced paths for sensitive output.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\ncert_bytes = b\"...\"\ntrusted_dir = tempfile.gettempdir()\n\nfd, tmp_path = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=\"acme-\", suffix=\".cert\", dir=trusted_dir)\ntry:\n    os.fchmod(fd, 0o600)\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as out:\n        out.write(cert_bytes)\n        out.flush()\n        os.fsync(out.fileno())\nfinally:\n    pass\n\nfinal_path = os.path.join(trusted_dir, \"acme.cert\")\nos.replace(tmp_path, final_path)\nos.chmod(final_path, 0o600)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ntempfile\nos\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [Python os.open documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html#os.open)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "dcd72da4-3bf6-3c47-9d8b-f374faf099a3",
              "name": "Hardcoded JWT Secret Or Private Key Used",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded JWT signing secret. In Python, embedding the key used by jwt.encode directly in application code exposes a credential that protects the integrity of every issued token. If the source code, logs, build artifacts, or repository history are accessed, an attacker can forge valid tokens and impersonate users.\n\nFor the shown sink, the signing key passed as the secret argument for HS256 should be loaded from a protected external source instead of being stored in code. A common baseline is reading the secret from an environment variable at startup and failing closed if it is missing. This keeps the credential out of the codebase and supports rotation without code changes.\n\nAlso ensure the token library usage matches the installed PyJWT version. Current PyJWT releases return a string from jwt.encode, so calling .decode() on the result is unnecessary and will fail in modern versions. Keep expiration and not-before claims, and protect the secret with restricted deployment-time configuration or a dedicated secrets manager.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nRemove JWT signing secrets and private keys from source code, test fixtures, and committed configuration files. Load them from protected runtime configuration such as environment variables, container secrets, or a managed secrets store, and deny startup when the value is absent or weak.\n\nLimit access to the secret, rotate it regularly, and use separate values per environment. Prefer asymmetric signing such as RS256 or ES256 when your architecture benefits from separating signing and verification keys, and store private keys with the same protections. Review repository history and CI logs for prior exposure and replace any compromised secret immediately.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\n\nimport jwt\n\nsecret = os.environ[\"JWT_SECRET\"]\nnow = datetime.now(timezone.utc)\nnot_after = timedelta(minutes=15)\n\ntoken = jwt.encode(\n    {\n        \"username\": username,\n        \"nbf\": now,\n        \"exp\": now + not_after,\n    },\n    secret,\n    algorithm=\"HS256\",\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nPyJWT\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-522: Insufficiently Protected Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/522.html)\n- [OWASP Secrets Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Secrets_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [PyJWT Usage Examples](https://pyjwt.readthedocs.io/en/stable/usage.html)\n- [Python os.environ documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/os.html#os.environ)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-522",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/522.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-522"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e28b869e-bbb8-3e20-938b-ec20c56f2edb",
              "name": "Flask App Running In Debug Mode",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure debug mode in a production web server. In Flask, calling app.run(debug=True) enables the interactive Werkzeug debugger, which can expose detailed stack traces, environment data, and in some configurations permit arbitrary code execution from the debug console.\n\nFor the shown sink, the application is explicitly started with debug mode enabled while also binding to a network interface and serving TLS material from local certificate files. Even if the host is intended to be limited, debug mode must not be enabled outside local development. Run the application with debug disabled, load the setting from a trusted configuration source, and use a production WSGI server for deployed environments instead of the built-in development server.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not hardcode debug=True in Flask startup code. Keep the debugger disabled by default and only enable it for local development through trusted environment-specific configuration. For deployed systems, run Flask behind a production-grade WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI, restrict network exposure, and ensure stack traces and interactive consoles are never accessible to end users. Also store TLS private keys outside temporary locations and apply file permissions that limit access to the service account.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    debug = os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\" and os.getenv(\"FLASK_ENV\") == \"development\"\n\n    app.run(\n        debug=debug,\n        host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n        ssl_context=(\"/tmp/acme.cert\", \"/tmp/acme.key\")\n    )\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation - Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Werkzeug Documentation - Debugger](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debug/)\n- [OWASP REST Security Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/REST_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e4ff3837-2451-3bba-bd07-2c6950436dae",
              "name": "Insecure HTTP Transport Used",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an insecure cleartext HTTP request. In Python, using requests.get() with an http:// URL sends the request without transport encryption, which allows network attackers to observe or modify traffic in transit.\n\nIn the sink shown, the request path includes user-derived data and is sent to a local service endpoint over HTTP. Even on internal or loopback-connected services, cleartext transport is a weak default because deployments often change, traffic may be proxied, and sensitive API responses or identifiers can be exposed. The fix is to call the endpoint over HTTPS and keep certificate verification enabled so the client authenticates the server before exchanging data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse HTTPS for all application-to-application requests, including internal service calls. Do not disable TLS certificate verification in requests, and configure the target service with a valid certificate trusted by the client. When dynamic data is inserted into a URL path, encode it safely before sending the request. Also set an explicit timeout so failed TLS connections do not hang indefinitely.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom urllib.parse import quote\nimport requests\n\nsafe_username = quote(username, safe='')\nr = requests.get(f'https://127.0.1.1:5000/api/post/{safe_username}', timeout=10)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nrequests\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insecure Transport](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Transport)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)\n- [Requests: SSL Cert Verification](https://requests.readthedocs.io/en/latest/user/advanced/#ssl-cert-verification)\n- [Python ssl module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/ssl.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "3.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e508a6cb-937f-3774-88fb-3c12971cfc03",
              "name": "Hardcoded Configuration Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded secret in application configuration. In Python web applications, embedding a Flask SECRET_KEY directly in source code exposes a sensitive value to anyone who can read the repository, build artifacts, logs, or deployment bundles. If this key is disclosed, attackers may be able to forge session data, tamper with signed cookies, or undermine other security features that rely on the application's secret material.\n\nFor the assignment shown, the secret is being set inline with app.config['SECRET_KEY']. Replace the literal value with a secret loaded from the environment or a protected configuration source at startup, and fail closed if the value is missing. This keeps the key out of version control and allows separate secrets per environment with proper rotation.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nStore application secrets outside the codebase in environment variables, a protected instance configuration file, or a dedicated secrets manager. Generate a long random value for the Flask secret key, keep different values for development and production, and rotate the key through your deployment process when exposure is suspected. Restrict access to the secret in CI/CD, container definitions, and runtime configuration, and avoid printing or logging the configured value.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\nsecret_key = os.environ.get(\"FLASK_SECRET_KEY\")\nif not secret_key:\n    raise RuntimeError(\"FLASK_SECRET_KEY environment variable is required\")\n\napp.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"] = secret_key\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Use of hard-coded password](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Use_of_hard-coded_password)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)\n- [Flask Configuration Handling](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#configuration-basics)\n- [Python secrets module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/secrets.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e54127ae-9b84-32eb-a017-f5d07467703d",
              "name": "Flask App Running In Debug Mode",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an active debug mode vulnerability. In a Python Flask application, running the development server with debug enabled exposes detailed error pages and the interactive debugger, which can reveal sensitive application state and may permit arbitrary code execution if it is reachable by an attacker.\n\nThe sink shown starts the Flask app with debug=True. That setting is intended only for local development. For this code path, disable debug mode explicitly and avoid relying on the built-in development server for deployed environments. Keep the host and port configuration if needed, but ensure the application starts without the debugger or automatic code reloader enabled.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not enable Flask debug mode outside local development. Start deployed applications with debug disabled and use a production WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI behind a reverse proxy. Keep framework and Werkzeug error details out of user-facing responses, and control behavior through environment-specific configuration so development settings cannot be promoted into production accidentally. Restrict local-only tooling to loopback interfaces and separate it from externally reachable deployments.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    app.run(host=\"127.0.1.1\", port=5001, debug=False, use_reloader=False, extra_files=[\"csp.txt\"])\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nN/A\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Werkzeug Documentation: Debugging Applications](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debug/)\n- [OWASP: Debug Code](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Debug_Code)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e54de0bd-3865-3a5f-a952-7e8a3be09677",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file handling. In Python, opening a predictable path such as /tmp/acme.csr can expose sensitive data or let another local user interfere with the file through pre-creation, replacement, or symlink attacks. Temporary files in shared directories must be created with secure APIs that generate unique names and restrictive permissions.\n\nFor the sink shown here, avoid reading from a hard-coded file in /tmp. Create the temporary file with Python's tempfile module, keep the returned handle or securely managed path, and read from that object instead of reopening a predictable filename. If the file must persist briefly, use NamedTemporaryFile or mkstemp with restrictive permissions and remove it promptly after use.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile, tempfile.TemporaryDirectory, or tempfile.mkstemp instead of hard-coded names under /tmp. Let the operating system generate an unpredictable filename, ensure the file is created atomically, and rely on the default restrictive permissions. Keep work in memory when practical, and if disk storage is required for certificate requests or other sensitive material, delete the file as soon as processing completes. Avoid following user-controlled paths or symlinks, and do not reopen temporary files by predictable names in shared directories.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nimport tempfile\n\nfd, temp_path = tempfile.mkstemp(suffix=\".csr\")\ntry:\n    with os.fdopen(fd, \"wb\") as csr_file:\n        csr_file.write(csr_bytes)\n\n    with open(temp_path, \"rb\") as csr_file:\n        csr_data = csr_file.read()\nfinally:\n    if os.path.exists(temp_path):\n        os.remove(temp_path)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\ntempfile\nos\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [OWASP: Insecure Temporary File](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Temporary_File)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e6f9ac4e-dc91-35df-9aae-ae99e96babc6",
              "name": "SQL Injection Via Raw SQL Query Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in Python database code occurs when untrusted values are merged into an SQL statement string before execution. In this sink, user-controlled data is inserted into an INSERT statement with Python string formatting, so crafted input can change the query structure instead of being stored as data.\n\nThe fix is to use parameterized queries and pass values separately from the SQL text. For Python DB-API drivers such as sqlite3, use placeholders and a parameter tuple. This lets the driver bind and escape values correctly, preserves types, and prevents attackers from injecting SQL through fields such as username or password.\n\nThis specific INSERT should not interpolate username or password into the SQL string. Keep the SQL statement static, use placeholders for every dynamic value, and pass the values in the execute call. If the application uses SQLAlchemy elsewhere, prefer bound parameters or ORM insert operations rather than building raw SQL manually.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not build SQL with string concatenation, %-formatting, f-strings, or format() when any part of the statement includes external input. Use the parameter style required by the Python database driver and pass data as a separate argument to execute(). Apply the same rule to SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, and bulk operations.\n\nWhere possible, centralize database access behind helper functions or an ORM so raw SQL construction is rare and consistently reviewed. Validate input for business rules such as length and allowed characters, but do not treat validation as a substitute for parameter binding. Also avoid storing plaintext passwords; hash them with a strong password hashing function before insertion.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nc.execute(\n    \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\",\n    (username, password, 0, 0, \"\")\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nsqlite3\nbcrypt\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [SQLAlchemy Textual SQL with bound parameters](https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/20/core/sqlelement.html#sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ea965aa1-f1e1-3989-93f9-be7439e48dd0",
              "name": "Missing Function Level Access Control",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis issue is missing function-level access control. In Python web applications, a view or handler that is reachable without enforcing authentication and authorization can allow users to call protected functionality simply by invoking the route directly.\n\nThe shown helper only extracts a username from a bearer token and returns None on failure. That is not enough to protect a sensitive endpoint by itself, because the caller must also reject unauthenticated requests and verify that the authenticated user has permission to perform the specific action. A secure fix is to enforce token validation at the entry point, fail closed with an HTTP 401 when authentication is missing or invalid, and perform explicit authorization checks before executing the protected logic.\n\nFor JWT handling, validate the token with a fixed algorithm list, require expected claims, and avoid broad exception handling that silently downgrades security decisions. Return structured errors instead of printing exceptions, and use a decorator or wrapper so every protected function applies the same access-control rules consistently.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nProtect every sensitive route with a shared authentication and authorization mechanism instead of relying on each function to remember to check headers manually. In Python, this is commonly done with a decorator, middleware, or framework dependency that validates the bearer token before the view runs.\n\nAfter authenticating the caller, enforce authorization based on the action being performed. Check roles, permissions, ownership, tenant boundaries, or other business rules explicitly, and deny access by default when the required privilege is absent.\n\nFor JWTs, accept only expected algorithms, validate expiration and subject claims, and catch specific token exceptions. Do not print raw token parsing errors to logs exposed to users, and do not continue execution when authentication fails. Keep secrets out of source code and load signing keys from secure configuration.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom functools import wraps\n\nimport jwt\nfrom jwt.exceptions import InvalidTokenError\nfrom flask import jsonify, request\n\nSECRET_KEY = \"change-me\"\nREQUIRED_ROLE = \"admin\"\n\n\ndef authenticate(req):\n    auth_header = req.headers.get(\"Authorization\")\n    if not auth_header:\n        return None\n\n    try:\n        auth_type, token = auth_header.split(\" \", 1)\n    except ValueError:\n        return None\n\n    if auth_type.lower() != \"bearer\":\n        return None\n\n    try:\n        payload = jwt.decode(\n            token,\n            SECRET_KEY,\n            algorithms=[\"HS256\"],\n            options={\"require\": [\"exp\", \"iat\", \"sub\"]}\n        )\n    except InvalidTokenError:\n        return None\n\n    return payload\n\n\ndef require_auth(role=None):\n    def decorator(view_func):\n        @wraps(view_func)\n        def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n            user = authenticate(request)\n            if user is None:\n                return jsonify({\"error\": \"authentication required\"}), 401\n\n            if role is not None and role not in user.get(\"roles\", []):\n                return jsonify({\"error\": \"forbidden\"}), 403\n\n            return view_func(user, *args, **kwargs)\n        return wrapper\n    return decorator\n\n\n@require_auth(role=REQUIRED_ROLE)\ndef protected_view(current_user):\n    return jsonify({\"message\": f\"hello {current_user['sub']}\"}), 200\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nPyJWT\nFlask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-community/Broken_Access_Control)\n- [OWASP Authorization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authorization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authentication_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-862: Missing Authorization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html)\n- [PyJWT Usage Examples](https://pyjwt.readthedocs.io/en/stable/usage.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-862",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/862.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-862"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ea97ea0d-3d9d-310e-bd68-dac366f7cebf",
              "name": "Insecure Deserialization Of Client Cookie Data",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUntrusted client-side session deserialization. This code rebuilds application state from a cookie using base64 decoding and json.loads, then trusts the result as a server-side session object. Because cookies are stored by the client, an attacker can modify the encoded JSON and submit forged state such as elevated roles, user identifiers, feature flags, or workflow status.\n\nIn Python, base64 is only an encoding layer and JSON parsing does not provide authenticity or integrity. The problem is not the parser itself, but treating client-provided data as trusted state after decoding it. For the sink shown, the fix is to stop loading authoritative session data directly from the cookie. Store the session on the server and keep only an opaque session identifier in the cookie, or at minimum verify the cookie with a server-held HMAC before accepting and decoding it.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not treat decoded cookie content as authoritative application state. Prefer server-side session storage backed by a database, cache, or framework session store, and place only an unpredictable session identifier in the cookie. Mark the cookie Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite as appropriate, and rotate session identifiers after authentication or privilege changes.\n\nIf client-side state must be used, protect it with a server-held signing key and verify the signature with hmac.compare_digest before decoding and parsing. Reject invalid, malformed, oversized, or unexpected payloads, and validate the resulting structure and allowed fields before use. Avoid storing sensitive or privilege-bearing fields in client-controlled cookies unless they are both integrity-protected and intentionally designed for that purpose.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport base64\nimport binascii\nimport hmac\nimport hashlib\nimport json\n\nSECRET_KEY = b\"replace-with-strong-random-secret\"\nSESSION_STORE = {\n    \"abc123\": {\"user_id\": 42, \"role\": \"user\"}\n}\n\n\ndef load_session(cookie_value: str) -> dict:\n    if not cookie_value:\n        return {}\n\n    session_id = cookie_value.strip()\n    session = SESSION_STORE.get(session_id)\n    return session.copy() if session else {}\n\n\ndef load_signed_cookie(cookie_value: str) -> dict:\n    if not cookie_value:\n        return {}\n\n    try:\n        payload_b64, signature_hex = cookie_value.split(\".\", 1)\n        expected_sig = hmac.new(\n            SECRET_KEY,\n            payload_b64.encode(\"ascii\"),\n            hashlib.sha256,\n        ).hexdigest()\n        if not hmac.compare_digest(signature_hex, expected_sig):\n            return {}\n\n        payload = base64.urlsafe_b64decode(payload_b64.encode(\"ascii\"))\n        data = json.loads(payload.decode(\"utf-8\"))\n        return data if isinstance(data, dict) else {}\n    except (ValueError, UnicodeDecodeError, json.JSONDecodeError, binascii.Error):\n        return {}\n\n\n# Preferred: keep trusted state on the server.\nsession = load_session(cookie)\n\n# If client-side state is unavoidable, verify integrity before loading.\n# session = load_signed_cookie(cookie)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nhmac\nhashlib\nbase64\nbinascii\njson\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Insecure Deserialization](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Deserialization)\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [Python hmac module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hmac.html)\n- [Python base64 module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/base64.html)\n- [Python json module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/json.html)\n- [CWE-345: Insufficient Verification of Data Authenticity](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/345.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-345",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/345.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-345"
                ]
              }
            }
          ],
